Gutach : even more safety for pedestrians
they are not 100 metres from each other : on Tuesday in Gutach , the new B 33 pedestrian lamp was put into operation at the village car park - in sight of the older town hall amphiles .
two plants so close to each other : intention or shields ?
yesterday , Gutachs Mayor clearly answered this question .
&quot; the town hall ramp was installed then because it secures the school path , &quot; Eckert explained yesterday .
the small traffic lights secure cyclists as well as bus passengers and the Bergle residents .
the plant officially opened yesterday is important for the Sulzbachweg / Kirchstraße cross @-@ section .
we have the museum , two churches , a spa park , a bus stop , a doctor and a bank as well as the flow of traffic from the residential area › Grub ‹ .
&quot; with high traffic and pedestrian traffic , the safety of which required another traffic light , &quot; said Eckert .
this is also confirmed by Peter Arnold of the Councillor Offenburg .
&quot; according to current measurements , around 12,000 vehicles pass through the municipality of Gutach every day , of which about ten percent are heavy goods traffic , &quot; says Arnold .
for this reason , the construction of another traffic light is more than necessary : &quot; safety simply goes ahead , &quot; says Arnold .
a total of four traffic jams were carried out , and a roundabout was also planned , but due to the enclosure in the area Sulzbachweg / Kirchstraße .
according to Arnold , everything was tested before when the traffic lights were located : &quot; by means of an extra @-@ long wooden trunks we discovered whether these vehicles could be driven out of the Sulzbachweg to the B 33 without cracking the traffic lights . &quot;
Arnold explained .
the system is equipped with colored LEDs that illuminate so strongly that the lights can be easily seen by car drivers , for example , even in the deep sun .
and it is also economical : older lighting systems consume about 100 watts , the new eight watts .
there are three lighting systems per direction .
Arnold explained the technology of the new plant : it is equipped with two radar sensors .
if the pedestrian presses the traffic light button , the upper radar sensor tests the traffic situation .
if the road is free , comes directly green for the pedestrian , if not , it takes about 15 seconds .
another radar sensor checks whether the green phase can be terminated for the pedestrian .
&quot; if a group or disabled people go through the streets , the green phase will be extended , so everyone will be able to travel safely through the tram , &quot; Arnold said .
of course , the driver has to take part as a partner here and watch the train .
this was not the case yesterday : hardly showed the traffic light for pedestrians green , smoked a top @-@ class vehicle - with bright red .
Josef Winkler has been writing for more than 30 years the needs of his childhood and youth from the soul .
the Kärntner poet has often described the catastrophes of his Catholic villainism - the lack of language , the tendency to rob violence and savage sexuality , the grandchildren and joylessness .
the winner of the Büchner Prize is known primarily as a prosaautor ; theatre texts are rar in his work .
Collage made of prosthetics Gerhard Fresacher creates a collage of prosthetics for his performance &quot; Weather lights on the tip of the tongue , &quot; which can now be seen in garage X at Petersplatz .
for example , the theatre maker combines elements from the autobiographic novel &quot; Der Leibeigenes &quot; ( 1987 ) with prosaminiums from &quot; Leichnam , his family belauernd &quot; ( 2003 ) .
on the largely empty stage - important Requisit : a shady sofa on which the sound is copied and masturbated - the eight @-@ headed ensemble is hanging through the text material .
Director Fresacher seems to have little faith in the text .
the 70 @-@ minute performance transmits the template with a wealth of registrations known from the repertoire of post @-@ dramatic forms of play .
the actors , in particular , are involved in the sometimes somewhat questionable sci @-@ fi transformations .
they are hardened hard , washed under the head under the water , torched with their dusk to the wall .
bound in Zellophan or rent , they stir on dangerously high sticks through the staging , either monologize them loudly or lie completely hidden on the stage floor .
however , the text hardly conveys itself in this tough way .
the best moments are the evening when sung - the bandwidth ranges from Deep Purple to popular limbs .
it is only towards the end that the overturned performance comes to calm , and Winkler &apos;s downright absurd humour appears .
a Blackbox in the Car ?
us road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the dwindling highway system , and believe that they have found the solution in a small black box that finds room in each car &apos;s dock .
the devices that record every kilometre and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the federal planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing US roads .
the usually boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colourful alliances .
libertaries have joined forces with environmental groups and are in favour of the government using small boxes to record the kilometres travelled - and possibly also where they were driven - and then using the information to calculate tax rulings .
the Tea Party is appalled .
the US Civil Rights Association ( ACLU ) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns .
but , while Congress cannot agree on action , several states are no longer waiting .
they are currently examining how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile .
thousands of car drivers have already tested the tachographs , some of which are equipped with GPS surveillance .
this really is a must for our country .
&quot; it is not something we will only possibly use , &quot; said Hasan Ikhrata , Managing Director of Southern California Assn . of Governments , who plans to record the mileage of all Californian drivers in the state from 2025 .
the way we pay these taxes will change .
the technology for this is there .
the initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund , financed from the taxes paid by US Americans at the tipping column , is bankrupt .
but America is no longer dancing as much as before .
cars consume less petrol .
government oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon ( less than 4 euro cents per litre ) has not increased for 20 years .
politicians do not dare to raise the tax by just one cent at high injections .
&quot; the gasoline tax is simply not sustainable , &quot; says Lee Munnich , an expert in transport legislation at Minnesota University .
his state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile @-@ based payment system .
he said .
bureaucrats call it a mile @-@ based user fee .
it is no surprise that the idea is shared by urban liberals , for the tax could be used , for example , to influence driving behaviour in such a way as to reduce congestion and harmful emissions .
Californian planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the federal state &apos;s ambitious , legally @-@ based climate change targets .
but the Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania , Chairman of the House Transportation Committee , has also said that he sees this as the most viable long @-@ term alternative .
the free distributors of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of letting drivers pay for their journey .
&quot; this is not a tax that disappears in a black hole , &quot; explains Adrian Moore , Vice @-@ President for Reason &apos;s guidelines .
people pay directly for what they get .
the movement is also supported by two former US Transport Ministers , who in a report in 2011 called on Congress to move towards mile @-@ based settlement .
last year , the US Senate approved a $ 90 million pilot project involving 10,000 cars .
but the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move , responding to the concerns of Members from rural areas who represent people who often have to spend many miles on their way to work or to the city in their daily lives .
several states and major cities nevertheless move in this direction on their own .
Oregon , who currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country &apos;s largest experiment , is the most committed .
these drivers will soon pay mileage fees to the state instead of the oil tax .
Nevada has already completed a pilot project .
new York City is also considering such a thing .
Illinois tests it to a limited extent with trucks .
and the I @-@ 95 coalition , which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast ( including Maryland , Pennsylvania , Virginia , and Florida ) , is currently studying how to introduce the amendment .
the concept is not a universal hit .
in Nevada , where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment , drivers were sceptical about the idea that the government could pursue any of its movements .
&quot; concerns about Big Brother and such things were a major problem , &quot; says Alauddin Khan , Head of Strategy and Results Management at the Ministry of Transport of Nevada .
people did not want it .
when the test started , the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website : &quot; it would be relatively easy to turn tachographs into sophisticated surveillance devices . &quot;
there is no need to build a gigantic , bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals .
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to capture the kilometres travelled , but not exactly when and where .
that would make the public more reassured .
hunting for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California .
the company did not originally enter to help states tax drivers .
on the contrary , its aim was to establish a foothold in an emerging market for motor insurance , in which drivers should pay on the basis of the mileage .
but the equipment she tests is also interesting for road planners , because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information , which is regularly uploaded via modem .
&quot; people are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded , &quot; said Ryan Morrison , Managing Director of True Mileage .
some of these public pilot programmes have made major mistakes .
there are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this .
in Oregon , planners experiment with giving car drivers a number of choices .
you can choose a device with or without GPS .
or they don &apos;t choose any device at all , and instead pay a flat @-@ rate fee based on the average mileage of all residents of the state .
others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by providing the devices with more functions than with smaller ones .
in New York City , traffic officials want to develop a tax @-@ based device that can also pay parking fees , pay insurance only for journeys of kilometres , and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time , so that drivers can avoid congestion .
&quot; drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system , &quot; says a city planning document .
some transport planners wonder , however , whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge diversion .
at the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for San Francisco Bay , officials said that Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by increasing fuel tax .
an additional one @-@ off fee or annual levy could be imposed on drivers using hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol , so that they too pay a fair share .
&quot; there is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is sufficient , &quot; explains Randy Rentler , the Commission &apos;s Head of Legislation and Public Affairs .
if we do that , hundreds of millions of car drivers worry about their privacy and many other things .
Königsfeld : small team beats up
the volunteer fire brigade managed their Herbsthauptprobe despite the lack of personnel with Bravour .
only eleven men took part in the exercise .
in his trial , Hans Kammerer chose the property Feder in Burgberger Straße .
a short circuit should have been created there .
two people were injured as a result of the fire and the development of smoke , but one of them was able to send an emergency call .
after the first examination of the facts by Hans Kammerer , two respirators of the Wehr were prepared to enter the building .
after a short time it was possible to find the first person and go to the outside .
the second person had to be worn .
this was not so easy , as a narrow staircase could be overcome .
the building , a workshop with integrated stables for two horses , was not easy to secure .
there was a lot of wood and straw basses in it .
there were also electrical machines for wood processing .
the first extinguishing attack took place via the tank in the vehicle .
a further line was made through a flood hydrants about 100 meters away .
three deletion attacks have now been designed .
a hollow beam tube was also used in the building .
Hans Kammerer was also interested in showing what to do with little available staff .
in case of a crisis , support is provided through the Königsfeld daily intervention group .
the commander was satisfied with the course of the exercise .
networking of universities and firms important
on his visit to the Landkreis Breisgau @-@ Hochschwarzwald , Landtag President Guido Wolf was also able to find out in Titisee @-@ Neustadt where the workers of tomorrow come from .
in the Hochschulzwald support centre , he studied this important issue together with the executive directors of the vocational schools and the Kreisgymnasium and the parent board chairman .
&quot; education is an important location factor , &quot; said Claudia Standarle , Director of the Hans @-@ Thoma School , who presented the networked education centre Hochschulzwald .
Wolf was impressed by the model projects for training .
since 2011 a successful cooperation has been established in the Walderstadt between the Förderzentrum , Kreisgymnasium and vocational school centre .
he also praised the family friendliness in the district .
&quot; it is important not only to look at the family phase , but also to look after family care due to demographic changes , &quot; Wolf said .
he also pointed out that more and more employees took care of the care and care of their families .
&quot; without the support of employers , the resulting burden on employees can lead to an end to the employment relationship , &quot; Wolf said .
but no one can afford to lose skilled workers , he continued .
another particularly important factor is the networking of universities and businesses .
&quot; for anyone who has already learned the benefits of the region during his studies , his acquired knowledge and his skills often remain with the regional economy , which helps to strengthen the region , &quot; said the President of the Country .
it is only by offering sufficient training places that skilled workers can be met .
in his opinion , the geographical advantage of the district is its favourable location in south @-@ west Germany , close to France and Switzerland .
he also experienced on his train journey from Titisee @-@ Neustadt to Freiburg the efforts already made to develop local public transport .
&quot; keep stubborn and make sure that public transport becomes better , &quot; he said .
