for 15 years the Kaul family has been inviting the Dietinger seniors to coffee , cakes and then a Vesper .
in the past , the elderly were brought to the resting place .
in the meantime , this afternoon will take place in St. Josef nursery .
the locals enjoyed the delicious cakes and torts .
later there were sausages .
Silvia kimmir @-@ Bantle and her father Karl kimmir entertained with popular melodies .
the more than 100 @-@ year @-@ old natural stone wall as the front boundary of the old church to the Kirchstraße is to be reinstated with the town of Bräunlingen .
in the days leading up to the Kilbig , a small walled wall , stabilizing and static discharge of the more than a hundred @-@ year @-@ old stone wall with balustrade , was installed during the first works of the renovation of the front school .
according to Alexander Misok of the Bräunlinger Stadtbauamt , the State Monument Office will be included in the plans and a rehabilitation concept for the old wall will be drawn up .
the aim is to calculate costs by experts who will then be put on the table to the Council of Ministers to decide and determine the way forward .
a decision on this is expected to be taken next year .
after the restoration , paving and planting of the old house of the school within the two sides of the school built in 1912 , a follow @-@ up measure must be taken in the foreseeable future to restore the barrier that is in need of restoration and to put it on new substructure .
the historic , one @-@ hundred @-@ year @-@ old wall of the old school to the Kirchstraße , is mainly due to water and frost damage , since there is no drainage , needs to be repaired and has a tendency to advance .
deep cracks in individual stones testify to weather damage , but the wall is not currently in danger of collapse .
a stable wall is a prerequisite for one of the students using Schulhof , which is the result of the current fastening work .
originally , schooling was planned even in 2008 / 2009 , but high unplanned expenditure caused a shift .
an important word about the historical school foundation , which has even been used for film recordings , will be the National Monument Office .
if guidelines come from this page , the city of Bräunlingen hopes to receive grants from the monument guards .
the students of the Bräunlinger primary school , who are now taught again in a well @-@ restored old school building with a new atrium , will soon be able to use the old school yard .
Özdemir wants to receive jazz education in Stuttgart
Cem Özdemir , President of the Federal Republic of the Greens , has now joined the ongoing discussions on the future of the music universities in Baden @-@ Württemberg .
&quot; I think it is wrong to abandon holistic education at the Musikhochschule Stuttgart , &quot; said Özdemir , &quot; Stuttgart News . &quot;
jazz and Classics are currently part of the Jazzplatz Stuttgart .
this contradicts Özdemir , who is considered a favorite of a direct mandate in the Bundestag elections on 22 September , the Green @-@ Red Government .
on the basis of an expert study , it is pushing for the reorganisation of the five high schools in Baden @-@ Württemberg .
after that , jazz and pop will be transferred from the Musikhochschule Stuttgart to the Musikhochschule Mannheim .
us border : &quot; super tunnels &quot; discovered for drug smuggling
on the border between Mexico and the US , investigators discovered and closed a &quot; super tunnel &quot; for drug smuggling .
as the US customs authorities informed , the tube between Tijuana and San Diego , which was more than 500 metres long , was equipped with electricity , railways and a ventilation system .
three suspects were arrested , eight tonnes of marijuana and almost 150 kilograms of cocaine seized .
according to the information , the tunnel had not yet been used .
&quot; these cartels are stupid if they think they could bury themselves under the radar , &quot; said Laura Duffy , US Secretary @-@ General at a press conference in San Diego , where an end to the tunnel had been discovered .
Duffy told drug gangs : &quot; if you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them , we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money . &quot;
both the US authorities and the Mexican security forces are in a permanent fight against drug cartels .
since 2006 , more than 77.000 people have been killed in Mexico in connection with drug crime .
designed by experts
due to the complex equipment of the tunnel , the investigators assume that it was constructed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year .
the track system was equipped so that electrically operated cars could be used .
on the Mexican side there is access to a building 80 meters from the border .
according to authorities , a ladder takes 20 meters into the depth to the actual tunnel entrance .
the tunnel has a cross section of 1.20 meters height and 90 cm width .
it would have been appropriate to promote illegal immigration to the United States .
two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the Cocaine Fund .
the third , a Mexican , was taken because of the confiscated marijuana .
as officials have said , all three are threatened with a maximum sentence of life imprisonment .
eight such tunnels have been discovered since 2006 , and the press conference in San Diego continued .
but this is the first time that cocaine has been found in such a tunnel construction .
cocaine is usually smuggled in smaller quantities and not through tunnels .
this shows the &quot; despair &quot; of drug gangs , whose traditional routes are now cut off , said Bill Sherman of the Drug Addiction DEA in San Diego .
they would do all they can to get to the US .
no details have been made known about the arrests , at least one of them being Mexicans .
they have to face imprisonment of up to ten years .
2014 : Geisinger Festival
the anniversary of the town of Geisingen on the occasion of the 1250 .
the return of the first mention is getting closer .
when the year ends in just eight weeks , the anniversary year is due .
Geisingen and Church Hausen were first mentioned together in 794 .
a document was produced in churches where both places are mentioned .
on 15 March , there will be an official launch for the anniversary year , and since Geisingen currently has no hall , this launch event will take place in the place where , 1250 years ago , both were first mentioned , in churches .
during the anniversary , numerous events are planned both in Geisingen and in churches .
churches @-@ Hausen will be held in July at a festive weekend from 18 to 20 July .
celebrate return .
on Friday with a party , on Saturday and Sunday with a festival around the Kirchtalhalle .
on this festive weekend there is also the Church House .
city Music Director Rudolf Barth has written a contract composition for the city on the occasion of the anniversary , which will be performed on three dates .
on 21 June , together with the Sunday celebration of the Black Forest Association , on 12 July in the Arena with fireworks and on 13 December as the first concert of city music in the new Festhalle .
this will be completed and inaugurated in the jubilee year , the official date is the last week of September 27 and 28 .
a new chronicle will also be released on the occasion of the Geisinger city anniversary .
&quot; however , it should be a chronicle not only of ghosts themselves , but also of a printed work on the ghost of today , which is made up of ghosts , churches @-@ Hausen , Leipferdingen , Aulfingen and Gutmadingen , &quot; says Mayor Walter Hengstler .
and today &apos;s ghost celebrates its birthday in 2014 , while in 1974 the present space was completed with the communitisation .
the new chronicle will be presented in Geisingen on 21 or 22 November .
2014 is another year with many jubilees .
the Narrenzunft Strohglonki starts on 8 February with a traditional dinner on the occasion of its 60 @-@ year @-@ old existence , the harmony Gutmadingen will be 90 years and will have the festival banquet on 29 March and will celebrate the district music festival from 1 to 4 May .
the Altenwerk Leipferdingen is 40 years old , the Geisinger school has been at the new location for 50 years and celebrates this on 10 May , the Kunstverein Polyhymnia Leipzig becomes 150 years old and celebrates this at the Brunnenfeste from 4 to 7 July .
the town of Geisingen was first mentioned in a gift certificate held by the monastery of St. Gallen in 764 .
the document was made in churches ( Hausen ) , which was a court .
both communities are therefore mentioned in the same document .
the reason for this 1250 @-@ year anniversary is that it is 40 years later .
Council targets track systems
should the railway transition &quot; Am Hirschen &quot; be extensively restructured to increase road safety ?
yes , the municipal councils have decided .
shield must take € 220 000 into account .
Deutsche Bahn intends to improve the Kinzigtal railway line next year .
in particular , safety at railway crossings is to be increased - regular collisions of trains with other vehicles occur throughout Germany .
if the municipalities agree to the conversion measures , they will have to pay one third of the costs , while the rest will be shared by the railways and the federal government .
Schiltach &apos;s mayor Roland Grießbearer explained to the Municipal Council the special features of the &quot; Am Hirschen . &quot;
there , the city plans to build a map at the height of the tunnelmundes west of the railway track .
larger vehicles , such as those transporting langholz , could also be on the opposite side without having to block the tracks .
therefore , Greeks proposed to construct a necessary support wall in such a way that the city could extend the subsequent road in due course to ensure a smooth flow of traffic .
this was controversial in the Council of Municipalities , because some Councils questioned the need for road proliferation : Thomas Kipp , in his statement , put the critics &apos; mood on the point : &apos; do we have to take so much money out of so few vehicles ? &apos;
Mayor Thomas Haas refuted : the railway crossing &quot; Hirschen &quot; was regularly used for long @-@ distance transport .
even wood from the Kuhbach area is partly transported over this route because the vehicles up to 20 metres long could not use the route at the Häberlesbrücke because they could not turn into the main road .
in addition , the route would serve as a route for those vehicles that are not allowed to use the tunnel when the main road is closed , argued Haas .
it should be assumed that Kirchberg- und Schlossbergtunnel would have to be restructured and rehabilitated , as is currently the case in Wolfach , that the railway transition &quot; Am &quot; Hirschen &quot; could also have an important traffic impact for a longer period of time .
the Councils agreed to examine the costs of the planned extension of the road .
in spite of this , the majority of the railway transition was approved , provided that the necessary support wall is built in such a way that the city could extend the road leading to &quot; Bahnhofstraße , &quot; where appropriate , to around 5.5 metres .
by contrast , the transformation of the railway crossing at Gerberei Trautwein could lead to a very different problem concerning access to the soaring Geroltzhäuser Weg .
the administration had asked the construction plans of the railway from the engineering office Breinlinger , since it had doubts as to whether the planned connection of Geroltzhäuser Wegs would be possible .
the investigation found that it was not possible to rule out the possibility that the inclination of the road could lead to longer vehicles being placed .
the responsibility for this is again borne by the city as a road builder .
the conversion could therefore lead to liability disputes .
as both the wooden descent and the bend worked in the current state of construction , one should not agree to the conversion of the railway , Haas argued .
at this point , the risk of a collision of the train with a vehicle on the transition is significantly lower than the other railway crossings , because there is a good visibility connection right next to the centre .
even trains from the main railway station should be held back at this point so that no collision could occur .
the majority of people refused to accept the conversion of this railway line because the city of Schiltach would have to &quot; bathe &quot; the problem with seated vehicles , according to the councils , since the railway could withdraw from responsibility after completion of the construction work .
the panel considers the conversion of the railway lines &quot; VorHeubach &quot; and &quot; VorKuhbach , &quot; which have already been concluded with the railway .
ESA decides on major space visions : missions for billions
distant planets , gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the coming years .
30 proposals were made , five are still in the race .
distant worlds .
astronomers have already found more than 1000 planets in other stars .
no one knows whether there are at least some lives .
the choice is difficult : should we look for gravitational waves ?
or would you prefer to explore the origin of the cosmos ?
or , after earth @-@ like planets , discover perhaps alien life ?
the people responsible for the European Space Agency Esa are asking these questions .
for their &quot; Cosmic Vision &quot; program , they are looking for ideas for two major space projects , which will make a decisive contribution to research .
the budget for such &quot; L missions &quot; is approximately EUR 1 billion each .
the start is expected to be 2028 and 2034 .
at the beginning of September , the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions .
thirty ideas have been discussed , five of which have now been shortlisted .
a number of bodies are examining the proposals , following up with researchers .
a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee in the next few days .
a total of four major questions have been chosen by the Esa , to which the missions of the programme &quot; Cosmic Vision &quot; launched in 2007 will find answers .
what are the conditions for the emergence of planets and life ?
the exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus the emergence of planets that surround these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness .
a large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness .
and if a star has planets , under what circumstances can life be created there ?
in order to address this issue , the space telescope &quot; Cheops &quot; will be launched in 2017 , which will examine more closely 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity .
the possibilities are limited , however , cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros .
with larger instruments , astronomers could depict Earth @-@ like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres , looking for &quot; biomarkers &quot; : gases that are considered to be an indication of biological activity .
how does the solar system work ?
this question , too , should ultimately clarify the conditions for the creation of life .
an important factor is the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field , as well as the partial radiation that it causes with the planetary system .
in our solar system , these processes can be investigated in an exemplary way .
with the Solar Orbiter , Esa has already approved a M @-@ class mission ( where the budget is about half a billion euros ) for this issue .
the probe should start in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the sun .
Jupiter and his monks are also of great interest to researchers .
you want to find out what role the giant planet has played in developing the solar system .
for this purpose , Esa provides the first of the three L missions of the &quot; Cosmic Vision &quot; program .
the probe &quot; Juice &quot; ( Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer ) is expected to start its journey in 2022 .
eight years later she reaches Jupiter and is supposed to study the atmosphere of the planet and the icy moon of Europe , KALLISTO and Ganymed .
what are the basic physical laws of the universe ?
the world offers many ways to study matter under extreme conditions and to examine whether the laws of nature we know are still valid there .
perhaps there are also deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united .
how did the universe emerge and what does it consist of ?
13.7 billion years ago our cosmos were created by the Big Bang .
in addition to the common matter of stars , planets and living beings like us , there are dark matter whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxies together , and dark energy , which accelerates the expansion of world space .
so far , researchers do not know what physical laws were in force in the first seconds of the Big Bang , nor what are dark matter and dark energy .
with &quot; Euclid , &quot; the Esa has already approved an M mission for 2020 .
with a special telescope , the probe is supposed to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the whole sky , thus providing insights into the nature of dark matter and dark energy .
who could do the race
of the 30 proposals , only two will remain at the end of the selection procedure .
many experts believe that the best chances of obtaining an L mission are &quot; E @-@ Lisa , &quot; an ambitious concept for detecting gravitational waves .
this means changes in the structure of the space time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago .
they have not been proved to date .
Elisa could do that , the scientists hope behind the project .
the mission provides for a detector consisting of two or three probes located in space .
in contrast to installations on Earth , he could also prove gravitational waves that emerged at the time of the Big Bang , thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos .
four other proposals compete for the second L mission : a large X @-@ ray telescope called &quot; Athena , &quot; which is to explore , among other things , black holes , &quot; Icy Planets , &quot; another mission to the outer planets of the solar system , &quot; Prism , &quot; a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation , &quot; Finlanet . &quot;
among other things , proposals for sampling back transport from Mars , for exploration of moon , Venus and asteroids , and solar physics are already out .
Snowden ready to &quot; cooperate &quot; with Germany on US surveillance
Edward Snowden , the whistleblower of the US intelligence service , has stated that he is ready to travel to Berlin and promise before the German Bundestag if the American National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander do not provide answers about their activities .
German MEP Hans @-@ Christian Ströbele met Snowden on Thursday in Russia , where he received this asylum to discuss with him the statement in Germany .
in a letter from Snowden presented to the media in Berlin on Friday , he wrote : &quot; although the result of my efforts has been demonstrably positive , my government continues to treat a dissenting opinion as a fidelity and is trying to criminalise political expression with a criminal offence where no defence is possible . &quot;
saying the truth is not a crime .
in the letter , Snowden writes that he is convinced that the support of the international community can convince the American Government to drop the charge against him .
the indictment brought by the US Department of Justice includes espionage and theft of state property .
German Interior Minister Hans @-@ Peter Friedrich said to Time Online : &quot; if Mr Snowden is prepared to talk to German representatives , then we will find ways to make this possible . &quot;
relations between the US and Germany are burdened by claims that the NSA has stopped Chancellor Angela Merkel &apos;s mobile phone .
Thomas Oppermann , the Member who leads the parliamentary committee responsible for the secret service , said that we should seize the opportunity to hear Snowden as a witness , if possible , &quot; without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the US . &quot;
Strobele , a member of the Greens , published an image of himself and Snowden in his Twitter feed .
he was accompanied by two German journalists during his visit to Russia .
flubele explained that , according to the lawyer of former NSA employee Snowden , he could not return to Russia if he left the country .
when Snowden says in Germany , he needs an assurance that he is &quot; safe &quot; there , he says .
Snowden says in his letter that he would be exposed to a &quot; serious and continuous &quot; campaign of persecution that has driven him out of his homeland .
but he is touched by the global response to &quot; my act of political expression . &quot;
citizens around the world , as well as senior politicians - including in the United States - have described revelations about an uncontrolled system of comprehensive surveillance as a public service .
in his letter , Snowden makes an offer of cooperation available to the German authorities &quot; when the difficulties surrounding the humanitarian situation have been resolved . &quot;
frontier Airlines charges handbaggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $ 100 for passengers who wish to collect hand baggage on their flight .
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $ 100 for a piece of hand baggage and $ 2 for coffee or limonade , even if it was stated in the announcement on Wednesday that passengers are likely to keep the whole dosage .
the new fee applies to hand baggage in the luggage box above the seat , small bags under the seat are still free .
Frontier explained that if the fee is paid in advance , the US $ 25 is calculated for travellers who only paid at the airport .
frontier Spokesperson Kate O &apos;Malley said that the fee of $ 100 aims to encourage travellers to pay in advance .
&quot; we do not want to calculate this sum , &quot; she said .
in 2008 , airlines started to charge for the first and second pieces of baggage .
passengers who tried to circumvent them have therefore placed as much as possible in their hand baggage , which means that baggage boxes above the seat are often overfilled .
fees are a way of encouraging passengers to take less on board .
O &apos;Malley said that the new fee is not really about earning money .
it is about the most loyal customers of Frontier , who have clearly stated that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find a place in the field above the seat .
passengers who buy their tickets on the airline &apos;s website do not have to pay .
this means that a passenger may be allowed to carry a piece of baggage free of charge at Frontier , but the next person must pay $ 100 for a comparable piece of baggage .
O &apos;Malley explained that Frontier &apos;s website and check @-@ in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the fee before they came to the airport .
Frontier &apos;s new hand baggage charge will only enter into force in summer , and there is no exact date yet .
passengers often use baggage allowances and other charges , but airlines like to use them .
they argue that the transportation of baggage should cost money and passengers should pay for this service if they wish .
many on Wall Street view the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses .
however , most have left the fingers of hand baggage charges .
spirit Airlines Inc . , the first charge for hand baggage three years ago , followed later by Allegiant Air , also a low @-@ cost airline .
the only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air , explained the airline consultant Jay Sorensen , who is closely following the additional fees .
in a December 2011 report , he estimated that the Spirit hand baggage allowance would bring $ 50 million annually .
Sorensen , who formerly held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines , recently fled with Spirit and was curious about what would be expected at the airlift if passengers were confronted with the company &apos;s unusual hand baggage charge .
&quot; the Boarding Process was one of the cleanest I have experienced in my career in aviation , &quot; he said .
I expected to see teeth and hands @-@ on discussions at the airlift .
&quot; the plane was full , &quot; he said , &quot; and boarding ran as if it was . &quot;
Frontier also follows Spirit with the $ 2 required for coffee , tea , lemonade or juice .
the company explained that passengers who bought lemonade or juice should keep all the cans and that coffee would be filled free of charge .
water is still free .
us Airways had been short @-@ lived in trying to demand money for soft drinks in 2008 , but this was reversed seven months later , after passengers complained and no other major company had followed suit .
frontline move to charge handbaggage if passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative aimed at directing customers to their own website .
airlines pay online travel agencies like orbitz 10 to 25 US dollars per ticket sold .
this provides an incentive for all companies to get passengers to buy directly from them rather than via an online travel agency .
but Frontier has gone furthest in this area .
in September , the company started to award half the number of frequent flyer miles when booking via an online travel agency .
on Wednesday , miles were cut back to 25 % of the flight .
for this reason , a flight with frontier over 1000 miles booked with a third party provider brings only 250 miles .
passengers can also reserve seats only when purchasing directly on the Frontier site .
Frontier has a loyal customer base in Denver , but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money .
the proceeds fell by 9 % and the flight capacity shrank by just 13 % in the first quarter , as stated in the financial report published on Wednesday by the parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc .
Republic has tried to control Frontier &apos;s finances in the context of the sale of society .
