NSA declares that an &quot; internal error &quot; and not hackers are to blame for the crashes of the website
the shadowy National Security Agency announced late Friday that an error had paralysed its public website some hours , not hackers , as was claimed online .
&quot; NSA.gov was not available this night for a few hours because an internal error occurred during a planned update , &quot; explained the spy agency in an email message .
the problem will be fixed this evening .
the claim that the failure was caused by a distributed denial of service attack ( DDoS ) is not true .
in the early evening hours , online server trackers noticed that the NSA website was not available for at least six hours and that this is still not available to some users .
prior to that , a NSA spokesman told ABC News that the sensitive internal network of the authority was &quot; in no way &quot; compromised .
secret information is not in danger , he said .
at least one group of hackers claimed to have paralyzed the NSA website with a DDoS attack .
in the event of such attacks , the target website is flooded with page views until the servers are overloaded and the website collapses .
cybertactic is relatively simple , and attacks do not serve to penetrate the target system &apos;s internal network .
the former super @-@ secret NSA , whose nickname was no search agency ( no such authority ) , is now in the public &apos;s light and is exposed to sharp criticism following the revelations that have been published in recent months about its extensive surveillance program at home and abroad - a result of the NSA &apos;s secret NSA data .
the growing controversy over the secret service fueled initial speculation that the incident today was the result of targeted cyber operation .
