loss of profit at Bombardier following decline in delivery figures and orders
on Thursday , Canadian aircraft and railway manufacturer Bombardier Inc reported a 15 % decrease in net profits after being pressurised by declining orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter , as well as contract problems in the railway sector .
Bombardier , based in Montreal , did not publish flight test data for his brand new CSeries aircraft and did not provide any new information on whether the aircraft could go into commercial use next September in accordance with the ambitious timetable .
so far , only three more startups followed the young @-@ distance flight of the test aircraft a year and a half ago , which makes it doubtful whether the test phase will be as planned .
the results fell short of forecasts and led to a fall of more than eight percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange .
Cameron Doerksen , an analyst at National Bank Financial , downgraded his assessment of &quot; outperform &quot; to &quot; sector &quot; on Thursday , with a limited exchange rate potential in the next one to two quarters .
&quot; while weaker aircraft delivery figures were expected to be as broad as possible , we are clearly disappointed by the development of the margins in the transport sector , &quot; Doerksen said in a customer letter .
we believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the test programme for the aircraft progresses .
however , if no new orders are announced in the coming months , we expect the market to become more sceptical about the programme .
Bombardier hopes that CSeries &apos; aircraft take @-@ off will be able to catapult the company into the lower market segment currently dominated by Boeing and Airbus .
the first test aircraft was presented to the public in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delays .
but , so far , binding orders for CSeries with 177 are moderate , as potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests and want to see whether the company &apos;s claims regarding fuel efficiency and cost savings of the new jet aircraft are correct .
there are currently 403 orders and commitments from 15 customers and companies .
CEO Pierre Beaudoin is confident that Bombardier will reach its target of 300 binding orders at the beginning of commercial use of the jet .
on Thursday , the management also assured analysts and media that the program was on schedule .
&quot; the test aircraft is no longer on the ground than expected , &quot; said Beaudoin at a telephone conference and added that ground tests and software updates were scheduled during the aircraft &apos;s standstill .
each manufacturer plans differently .
we have decided to take a first flight and then attach a review period , as we have done .
this is happening throughout the programme .
the second of five test aircraft is expected to start in the next few weeks , the remaining one shortly thereafter , was said by the company side .
nevertheless , analysts remain sceptical as to whether , twelve months after the maiden flight , the first customer can start operating a CSeries aircraft .
Bombardier explained that it is reviewing the planning for commissioning ( EIS ) and will update it in the coming months .
&quot; the slow progress of the flight test - even though it appears that they correspond to BOMBARDIERS internal planning - reinforces our view that the start @-@ up is moving to the first quarter of 2015 , &quot; Doerksen said .
in the third quarter with the end of September 30 BOMBARDIERS net profit fell to $ 147 million or $ 8 cents per share of $ 172 million or 9 cents per share in the previous year .
the adjusted profit per share remains 9 cents .
sales fell slightly from 4.2 billion dollars to 4.1 billion dollars .
analysts had expected a profit of 10 cents per share and a turnover of 4.56 billion dollars , according to Thomson Reuters I / B / E / S.
the world &apos;s fourth largest aircraft manufacturer says that he delivered 45 aircraft this quarter , a decrease of 57 last year .
net orders were from 83 aircraft to 26 .
the order book in the aerospace sector was $ 32.9 billion on 30 September , unchanged from 31 December .
&quot; in the aerospace sector , the results were in line with our requirements , but low order intake and overall market conditions were disappointing , &quot; said Beaudoin .
revenues in the aerospace sector fell 13 percent to $ 2 billion .
Bombardier , the world &apos;s largest railway manufacturer , announced that revenues in this business grew by just under 11 % to $ 2.1 billion .
the order book in the transport sector was $ 32.6 billion on 30 September , slightly increasing from 31 December .
the profit margin in the transport sector was affected by resolution problems in some major contracts .
according to corporate governance , there will be new benchmarks for the fourth quarter .
in the afternoon trading on Thursday , the Bombardier share plummeted by 8.5 % and stood at 4.83 Canadian dollars , after it was also announced that the Google Finance Board will change to the Board of Directors Patrick Pichette .
