cocaine @-@ dependent lawyer who warned drug boss against police investigation must go to prison
Basharat Ditta , 42 , gave information to Neil Scarborough
the lawyer was afraid that his secret drug addiction could come to light
he was sentenced to three years in prison by Liverpool Crown Court
a well @-@ known criminal defender who warned a drug baron against a major police investigation because he was afraid that his secret drug addiction could be exposed was sentenced to three years in prison .
Basharat Ditta , 42 , gave Neil Scarborough the underworld with sensitive information about his drug @-@ trafficking activities after he was compromised by his own cocaine addiction .
the lawyer praised by criminals as &quot; first class &quot; with the nickname &quot; Bash &quot; was arrested in his house in 2011 after the police oversaw Scarborough , which he had represented in an earlier drug procedure .
officials observed how Scarborough ( 32 ) delivered three Beutel Kokain at the lawyer &apos;s house in Blackburn , Lancashire , while he was with colleagues at a meal of the Bar .
the investigation revealed that Ditta regularly consumed class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in its hair , wallet and credit cards .
over a period of eight months between January and August 2011 , he attempted to obtain unauthorised information on the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners .
all four suspects were then monitored by the police under a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire , Cumbria , Merseyside , Berkshire and West Yorkshire .
together with 32 other people , they were later arrested after the police secured £ 1.5 million in cash in a series of house searches for heroin and cocaine .
ditta , 42 , passed on information to the criminals because he feared that his drug addiction could be publicised .
today , Ditta , who works for the firm Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn , was found guilty and convicted at Liverpool Crown Court following a three @-@ week trial on two charges for obstructing the judiciary .
he gave up cocaine ownership during an earlier consultation .
the lawyer was transferred after the police found out in their investigation of Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011 .
two investigators followed the suspect and saw how he went to Ditta &apos;s house , where drugs were placed under the lawyer &apos;s garbage with a purity of 60 % .
shortly after he delivered the drugs , Scarborough regularly contacted Ditta , who was at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park .
the lawyer returned home , took drugs and nine communications were exchanged between the two .
it became known in court that Ditta was a &quot; regular consumer &quot; of cocaine after tests of class A drugs discovered in his hair , wallets and on his credit cards .
ditta was later arrested , but refused to take cocaine and said that he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client , claiming that her discussion was subject to &quot; lawyer secrecy . &quot;
during his arrest , Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards , but they were secured and he was taken from a hair sample .
at the time of police interrogation , he stated that he was running an office under his private address as well as in the workplace , and clients would call him at home for legal matters .
it became known in court that he had appealed to key players in the drug trade , some of whom he had previously represented , after significant arrests and informed about what the investigators knew about them .
prosecutor Anne Whyte said : &quot; a criminal lawyer should know better than anyone else that the law is not broken . &quot;
ditta is accused of abuse of his position as a criminal defender , because he has entered too much with certain clients .
the relationship in question is not simply a drug trader , but a drug trader who supplies his lawyer with drugs .
some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate , because he was the lawyer of these people .
but that went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between lawyer and client .
he acted as far as possible to prevent police investigations so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities .
Mr Ditta thus discredited his profession .
he was too close to certain clients , especially Scarborough , and he allowed his independence to be compromised .
ditta dismissed any misconduct and claimed : &quot; if I were a corrupt lawyer , what I am not , and wanted to pass on information to Scarborough , I would not wait 15 hours , but do so immediately . &quot;
but , after the hearing , Superintendent Lee Halstead of the police in Lancashire said : &quot; Mr Ditta took the step from a criminal defender to a criminal at the moment he started buying drugs from organised criminals . &quot;
his cocaine addiction led to a hopeless compromise and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organised crime , who asked him to obtain valuable information on police investigations .
lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure public confidence and confidence .
ditta missed this trust and tried to hide behind the facade of his profession .
Lancashire &apos;s Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation against Ditta , which also led to a conviction in three cases for the possession of cocaine and judicial impairment , underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice .
this case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law .
we find you and bring you to justice .
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after he declared himself guilty of the conspiracy to trade in heroin , cocaine and cannabis .
thirty @-@ five more people involved in drug trafficking have been sentenced to a total sentence of 153 years for drug offences .
on his website , Ditta published an area of questions and answers about himself in which he indicated that his dream job was to represent clients in the death cell in America , his ultimate guest at dinner was Mohammed Ali and opportunity inequality was the motivation for his work .
