children &apos;s dreams come true
the kindergartens and nurseries in the customs district will receive mail these days .
in cooperation with Bauhaus and Sparkasse Zollernalb , the Schwarzwälder Bote wishes to assist the institutions in realising their construction and beauty wishes .
does the kindergarten need a new sandbox ?
all kindergartens , nurseries and crèches from the entire customs group can participate in the action .
if you have a desire for construction or beauty for your facility , you can apply for it at the Black Forest Bows .
be creative with your children and surprise the jury of the Action Kindergarten @-@ Baustelle .
a jury made up of representatives of Black Forest Bote , Bauhaus and Sparkasse Zollernalb , selects three wishes from all entries .
what are the conditions for participation ?
the wish should be realised with construction material of a maximum value of EUR 2000 and on a day ( action ) .
in addition , the winner himself must provide for many hard @-@ working builders .
what about the day of action and the helpers ?
Bauhaus provides the material with the support of Sparkasse Zollernalb .
it is delivered to the kindergarten on the agreed day and is then to be processed directly by the helpers .
helpers can be parents , grandparents , friends , clubs and of course the educators and children themselves .
Kenyan press outraged at controversial media law
&quot; we are in a frightening situation and we should ask ourselves : what does Parliament stop from simply abolishing judicial independence tomorrow ? &quot; was stated in the newspaper , which considers the draft law not constitutional .
&quot; the law is draconian and very punishable and we reject it , &quot; said Cyrus Kamau , Managing Director of the Capital Group , including CapitalFM , one of Kenya &apos;s most prestigious independent radio stations and news websites .
he said that the new media tribunal &quot; will always be biased , because it is an extended arm of the government , &quot; and restrictions on content and advertising would damage Kenya &apos;s position in the global economy .
he said .
according to The Star , the new law &quot; effectively puts the media in a hurry . &quot; by contrast , The Standard , Democracy , and Freedom of Speech in Kenya wrote &quot; a heavy blow &quot; and called it &quot; draconian . &quot;
the adoption of the law is one of a series of measures aimed at strengthening national security in the aftermath of the attacks by armed Islamists on the Westgate shopping centre in September .
the Kenyan media attracted the anger of the authorities by publishing pictures of security cameras showing how the units sent to the scene allegedly wiped out the luxurious shopping centre .
police chief David Kimaiyo responded by hiring two journalists and a leading media representative , even though the charge was withdrawn following a media outcry .
under the new law , media houses can be fined up to 20 million Kenyan shields , and individual journalists with up to one million and the further risk of losing their professional recognition or being excluded from official press accreditation .
the Tribunal also has the right to confiscate the possession of the persons concerned if a penalty is not paid .
according to the Daily Nation , &quot; a single punishment can push most radio stations into bankruptcy . &quot;
moreover , the newspaper believes that these measures could have a devastating effect on Kenya &apos;s &quot; lively blogosphere &quot; description .
if they silence the media , politicians could do whatever they want with impunity .
&quot; no one will ever know it , &quot; wrote Mutuma Mathiu , a journalist at the nation , who calls the Kenyan media a crucial control factor in public life .
&quot; leave politicians , lead the country into bankruptcy and return us to the time of hunters and collectors , &quot; he commented .
the Kenyan legislators have in the past attracted public anger .
in May , they voted to reverse the cuts ordered by the National Compensation Commission and put back their defective salaries of around 532,000 schilling bills per month - among the highest in the world .
