security concerns in Mozambique are growing in the face of clashes between influential figures
thousands of people gathered in the centre of Maputos under the watchful eyes of the statue of Samora Machel , the founder of the state and first president of Mozambique to agree to peace calls during a rare public demonstration .
&quot; we want peace again , we want stability , &quot; said Vanessa de Sousa , Managing Director of an investment company .
for fear of the country &apos;s future , she exchanged her business clothes for a T @-@ shirt with the inscription &quot; We demand security &quot; in Portuguese and joined the crowd on Thursday on the capital &apos;s independence square .
for two weeks , there have been reports almost daily of clashes between government forces and RENAMO , which are among the worst battles since the peace agreement over 20 years ago .
RENAMO was once a notorious rebel movement , initially supported by the White @-@ dominated Rhodesia and later by South Africa &apos;s apartheid government in an effort to destabilize the country &apos;s independent government .
after the 1992 peace agreement , it became an opposition party .
analysts consider it unlikely that the country will return to an extended conflict , but recent events have worried foreign investors and locals .
a lot is at stake for the fast @-@ growing economy , because the discovery of huge reserves of gas off the coast and coal farmers in the northwest could bring investment of more than $ 50 billion from companies like Rio Tinto , Vale from Brazil , Eni from Italy , and Anadarko from the US in the coming years .
the ruling Frelimo Party , the dominant force since 1975 , and RENAMO blame each other for the tensions .
RENAMO claims that the government provoked the recent clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala , a traditional stronghold of Renamos , on 17 October .
the attacks on former rebels escalated when government forces attacked RENAMO bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama , the leader of the group , Renamos spokesman to the Financial Times .
the government blames RENAMO for the clashes and accuses the organization of attacking soldiers .
President Armando Guebuza has tried to downplay concerns about instability .
on Wednesday , he told AFP , the French news agency , that Dhlakama sees himself as a &quot; loser , &quot; who &quot; wants to use all his remaining forces to prove that he can impose his decisions on the government . &quot;
both Frelimo and RENAMO stress that they want to avoid war .
but concerns have increased since Mazanga was quoted as saying that RENAMO is abandoning the 1992 peace agreement .
he explained to FT that he meant that Frelimo no longer respected the agreement .
&quot; our vision is to resume negotiations and to do so seriously , &quot; said Mazanga .
earlier talks between the parties have done little to resolve the tensions caused by a series of clashes this year .
&quot; we have here two adult men ( Guebuza and Dhlakama ) who meet the heads , &quot; says Joseph Hanlon , lecturer at Open University and Mozambique expert .
none of them is good at negotiating and no one is prepared to make the necessary concessions .
RENAMO , who is pressing for electoral reform , has already said that she will boycott the local elections in November .
presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year .
some commentators interpreted the use of force as an attempt by a stifling movement to obtain concessions and financial benefits from the government .
Renamos electoral success has shrunk since 1992 , while a newer party , Movimento Democrático de Moçambique ( MDM ) , founded by a former RENAMO member , is likely to improve in the elections .
Mazanga claims that Guebuza - whose resignation is due when his second term ends next year - wants to destroy the country &apos;s democracy .
&quot; he does not want a multi @-@ party democracy , he does not want a transparent election , he does not want peace because he does not want to give up the presidency , &quot; said Mazanga .
it is unclear what capacity RENAMO has , but it has taken unrest attacks on police stations and vehicles on an important North @-@ South link .
most battles took place in the province of Sofala , which is located a few hundred kilometres north of Maputo , but in which Beira is located , the port , mining companies such as Rio Tinto and Vale for the export of coal .
in June , Rio stopped using the railways for one month after RENAMO announced an attack on the track .
Mazanga responded cautiously to the question of whether RENAMO would repeat this threat .
RENAMO wanted to &quot; warn the international community that things are not good in Mozambique , &quot; said Mazanga .
instability has increased frustration with the government , says Fernando Lima , Head of Mediacoop , an independent media company , because many people have already been worried about corruption , slow progress in development , and a recent wave of kidnapping .
&quot; people think that the government and the president are responsible for the country &apos;s future and should be the one who finds solutions to the problems , &quot; he explains .
Omar Sultane , a demonstrator , said that people simply wanted stability .
&quot; no one is interested in RENAMO and Frelimo , they just want peace and usable roads , &quot; he said .
children should receive myths and legends as &quot; models for life , &quot; says an author .
Thor &apos;s stories showed that &quot; brutal power has no chance against clever tricks , &quot; and the Artus legend demonstrates how important it is to have a dream .
however , many of the myths are &quot; far too wild , too offensive , and , in some cases , too dirty to be taught at schools , &quot; which is why Crossley @-@ Holland called for &quot; careful selection &quot; of age @-@ appropriate works .
&quot; I find it wonderful that myths and folklore are already part of education in America , &quot; he said .
I have proposed this as a plan for twenty years .
he added that &quot; overly didactic &quot; authors and teachers would &quot; shut down &quot; children , because in entertaining stories the embassies would be conveyed &quot; underground . &quot;
Crossley @-@ Holland , who translated Beowulf from the Anglo @-@ Saxon language and is the author of the Penguin Book of Norse Myths and the British Folk Tales , said : &quot; you can pursue certain intentions , but you should keep them in the background . &quot;
perhaps the greatest difference between an adult author who writes for adults and an author who writes for children lies in the need to convey hope .
not everything must be simplified or lead to the happy end , but there is an immanent sense of good and evil .
this must be shown underground , through which history is revealed and not explained .
this is the old story of showing instead of counting .
Hansjakob moves again in FREIHOF
100 years ago Heinrich Hansjakob moved to Haslach , on Sunday his last years in the &quot; FREIHOF . &quot;
the many spectators were enthusiastic about the extremely short @-@ lived scene game .
from the arrival , to the award of honorary citizenship to his death , the screenwriter and Hansjakobactor Alois Kraftzcyk had designed a entertaining piece that received much praise under the direction of Cornelia people .
Marcus Zagermann took the audience as a spokesperson with the ten different scenes , explained contexts and bridled periods from youth to approaching retirement .
on October 22 , 1913 Hansjakob returns home to his children &apos;s skies , in his FREIHOF .
and then began the scene game in which Alois Krafczyk once again shines in his paradise as a great son of the city .
