Ben Greenman : ten Years New York Comedy Festival : the New Yorker
one might say that New York City is the birthplace of Stand @-@ up Comedy in America : almost a hundred years ago , the variable artist Frank Fay , who worked as Conférencier at the Palace Theatre am Broadway , began to tell the crowd directly jokes in the form of a conversation .
over the years , Fays &apos;s innovation has been enhanced , as was the last time at the New York Comedy Festival .
launched and led by Caroline Hirsch , founder of the stand @-@ up institution Carolines , this year the festival celebrates its tenth anniversary with over sixty shows in small clubs and large theatres .
&quot; most of these headliners began with Carolines and then became more and more successful until they were known at some point to appear in a club , &quot; said Hirsch .
we have designed this festival so that we can continue working with them .
at this year &apos;s event there are performances by Wanda Sykes , Kathy Griffin and Bill Maher , as well as by &quot; Stand Up for Heroes , &quot; an annual music and comedy charity event for army veterans at Madison Square Garden , which includes Bruce Springsteen , Jon Stewart , Roger Watsers and Bill .
with the festival the world of comedy has also grown .
a number of comedians participating in the festival this year have become known about more unconventional ways , such as broadcasts on smaller TV channels such as Comedy Central , FX and Spike .
Nick Kroll became known with a Sitcom on cable TV ( the ironic @-@ sounding fantasy football series &quot; The League &quot; on FXX ) and now has his own sketch show on Comedy Central .
Jenny Slate was part of the match at &quot; Saturday Night Live &quot; and &quot; Parks and Recreation , &quot; although she is best known for her viral video series &quot; Marcel the Shell with Shoes On . &quot;
both Kroll and Slate and other young comedians with characteristic voices ( the surreal pessimistic Anthony Jeselnik , the ironic , racial @-@ centred W. Kaumau Bell ) are products of the decentralized world of American comedy .
one of the biggest visitors of the festival is an interview : David Steinberg speaks to Larry David .
Steinberg started as a stand @-@ up comedian , but has become a prestigious television and film director and an unofficial comedy historian .
from 2005 to 2007 , he hosted a TV show entitled &quot; Sit Down Comedy with David Steinberg &quot; at TV Land .
the meeting takes place in the Town Hall in the middle of Manhattan .
&quot; the city is definitely in the comedy DNA of Larry &apos;s entire work , &quot; said Steinberg .
he told me if he is here , then he sometimes goes through the street between two buildings and thinks : hey , if I lose all my money , then perhaps I live here .
