Court blocks decision on NYPD &apos;s Stop and Frisk Directive
on Thursday , a Federal Court of Appeal in the United States blocked the order of a judge who had demanded changes to the Stop and Frisk Program ( &quot; Continuing and browsing &quot; ) of the New York Police Department , and withdrew the judge from the case .
the second US Appeal Court declared that Judge Shira Schlüdlin &apos;s decisions would be suspended until the city had been invoked .
in August , the judge ruled that the city was in breach of the Constitution by the way in which the program for stopping and questioning people was implemented .
the city appealed against its assessment and the remedies ordered , including the decision to set up a supervisory body to assist the police in amending its directive and its training programme .
the Appeal Court heard the arguments on the suspension requested on Tuesday .
the Appellate Report stated that the judge had to be relieved of the case , because it had breached the Code of Conduct for US judges by stipulating that a judge should avoid the appearance of partiality , partly due to a series of media interviews and public statements in which she publicly responded to the Court &apos;s criticism .
the judge ruled that police officers violated the civil rights of tens of thousands of people because they inappropriately targeted black and Latin American men with the Stop and Frisk programme .
it appointed an external supervisor to monitor the implementation of major changes , including reforms in directives , training and service supervision , and ordered a pilot programme of cameras on the body in quarters where most controls were carried out .
in August , the city of New York agreed to end the practice of storing names and addresses of people who were released again after police control .
an oral hearing to appeal the city is scheduled after 14 March 2014 .
the Stop and Frisk tactic has been criticized by a number of citizens &apos; rights defenders .
controls of this kind have been in various forms for decades , but the number of recorded controls during the term of office of the non @-@ partisan mayor Michael Bloomberg has risen to a total of 684,330 in 2011 , most of them black and Latin American men .
in 2004 , four men belonging to all minorities brought an action which became a collective redress .
advocates of changes to the NYPD &apos;s Stop and Frisk program say that the changes will end unfair practices , create a more trustworthy and effective police force , and influence the way other policemen use the regime .
opponents believe that the changes would dampen the morality of the police , but not criminality ; nor would money be wasted and the broader problem of a police force under pressure after thousands of posts have disappeared in the last decade .
the judge pointed out that she did not end the Stop and Frisk practice , which is constitutional , but only the way in which the NYPD implemented controls .
