NSA revelations reinforce company paranoia over state supervision
on a mild day at the end of August , a German police helicopter flew deep across the US consulate in Frankfurt am Main , Germany &apos;s financial capital .
on the instructions of the Federal Office for Constitutional Protection and Counter @-@ Terrorism ( BVT ) , the German Interior Intelligence Service , he should photograph the roof of the US outpost , which is less than 5 km from the European Central Bank and the Bundesbank .
according to German media , the BVT wanted to prove the presence of surveillance antennas and the action led to a change of speech between the US and the German Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Berlin .
James Clapper , US Director of National Intelligence , once again insisted in September that the US did not use foreign espionage opportunities &quot; to steal the business secrets of foreign companies on behalf of US companies to enhance their international competitiveness or profits . &quot;
but since Edward Snowden , the former worker who has become a whistleblower , began to publish his fillings of US surveillance secrets , European governments and business leaders have become unsure whether they can take the director at their word .
reports that the American National Security Agency has spied out the Brazilian oil company Petrobas and acquired data from American cloud providers , including Google and Yahoo , have brought the company paranoia to a new level because of state surveillance .
the barrel to overflow brought the revelation that Chancellor Angela Merkel &apos;s phone had disappeared , possibly for ten years .
if the most powerful person in Europe can be targeted , then it is certain that corporate governance will also be possible .
Snowden has made intensive cooperation between US intelligence services and companies transparent .
I believe that it is conceivable that these data will be used for mutual benefit .
&quot; Germany must wake up , &quot; explains Oliver Grüner , President of BITMi , representing small and medium @-@ sized IT companies in Germany .
German companies believe that the US is now almost as risky as China when it comes to industrial espionage and data theft , according to a survey published by the consultants EY in July .
however , in the documents leaked through by Snowden , there has been no evidence so far that the US has passed on the business secrets of foreign companies to its own companies .
politicians have expressed concern that the EU lacked certain IT and Internet capabilities and should reduce its dependence on the US .
companies are sceptical about this .
the Bundestag proposed that we should build a German Google .
I can only close my eyes and open them slowly ...
&quot; this is not how it works , &quot; says Hasso Plattner , Chairman of the German software manufacturer SAP .
if we had wanted a strong European IT industry , we should not have let it die 20 years ago .
everything in Germany is subsidised , from coal to cars to agriculture .
everything except the IT industry .
nevertheless , the scope and technical refinement of the US spy agencies revealed by the Snowden revelations shocked companies that had previously seen China &apos;s largest spy risk .
cloud computing is undergoing a major change because European business leaders are now more aware that data stored in the US is subject to jurisprudence and therefore potentially at risk .
according to a survey conducted by the Cloud Security Alliance , a commercial institution , around 10 % of non @-@ US members planned to use an American supplier following revelations about US data mining activities with Prism .
Jim Snabe , Deputy Managing Director of SAP , says : &quot; we see a new question from customers who did not exist a year ago - where are my data stored and can you guarantee that they will remain physically in this legal area ? &quot;
many German business leaders take the view that the latest reports simply confirm what they already knew , namely that powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets and that they must therefore be guarded at all costs .
it is no surprise that economic espionage is taking place .
that has always been the case .
&quot; it has been a topic for many years and has not changed fundamentally due to the current discussion , &quot; says Kurt Bock , Chairman of the chemical company BASF .
the Americans are spying on us at commercial and industrial level , just as we do , because it is in the national interest to defend our businesses .
corporate governance usually does not talk about the counter @-@ measures that have been taken , because that gives benefits to attackers .
in large companies , employees have long been aware that taking a free USB stick at a fair or leaving a laptop in the hotel room is not advisable , to say the least .
Ulrich Hackenberk , Executive Board member of Audi , says that it has been a standard practice for years to collect mobile phones before a board meeting so that they cannot be used as interception devices .
the German BVT advises executives to use simple prepaid phones when travelling abroad because smartphones may be compromised .
prepaid phones are thrown away afterwards .
however , there is concern that small and medium @-@ sized enterprises remain vulnerable to hacking and surveillance .
in Germany , many of these companies are world leaders in their respective niches .
&quot; small and medium @-@ sized enterprises often lack the experience , staff and financial resources to effectively protect business secrets against unauthorized access , &quot; says BVT in a report .
the US warns its own firms against economic espionage by other countries .
according to Washington Post , in February , in the US National Intelligence Estimate , France , Russia , and Israel rank two of the countries that used to acquire the economic data of hacking .
a member of the board of a German blue chip company agreed to &quot; the worst &quot; when it comes to economic espionage .
Bernard Squarcini , former head of the French internal intelligence service DCRL , was quoted in an interview this month : &quot; the secret services know very well that all countries , even if they cooperate in the fight against terror , spy on their allies . &quot;
