CDC publishes school allergy guidelines
on Wednesday , the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention ( CDC ) published a series of guidelines for dealing with children &apos;s food allergies in schools .
these are the first such guidelines issued by the US administration , as the number of children with food allergies is increasing .
one in 20 children in the United States now has a food allergy .
according to CDC , the spread of food allergies among children increased by 18 % between 1997 and 2007 .
the guidelines provide information for schools to raise awareness among teachers and staff of food allergies and how to deal with children who have allergic reactions .
it is also recommended that schools have Epinephrine in front - the epiPen car injection is used most frequently - to counter a potentially deadly hypersensitivity reaction .
legislators in the federal states have recently amended the rules to make it easier for schools to hold Epinephrin .
the report also contains a list of typical symptoms mentioned by children with allergic reactions .
children may say : &quot; it feels like something is pressing on my tongue , &quot; &quot; My tongue feels like a hair is lying on it &quot; or &quot; My tongue cribs . &quot;
parents of Intersexual Children can choose &quot; sex undetermined &quot;
Germany is the first European nation to recognise a third gender for children born with unclear genitals .
newborn babies are no longer assigned rigidly male or female .
under the new law , parents no longer have to declare sex for such children , but can specify &quot; undefined &quot; or &quot; not defined &quot; on the birth certificate .
the aim of the law is to take the pressure from parents , so that they do not have to take hasty decisions regarding sexual allocation operations in newborn children , and to combat discrimination against intersexual people .
an intersexual person said , according to BBC years later , &quot; I am neither man nor woman . &quot;
I stick to the patchwork created by doctors , mutilated and full of scars .
it is estimated that one in 2,000 children are neither young nor girls .
they are among the intersexuals , a group that is covered by the diagnosis of &quot; sex differentiation disorder &quot; ( DSD ) , a collective term for people with atypical chromosomes , germs ( ovaries or trousers ) , or unusually developed genitals .
Wallis Simpson may have been intersexual .
the understanding of gender identification is still not very well developed , but most US experts suggest that the best available gender information should be used if a provision is not possible , rather than waiting for the child &apos;s psychological and physical development before deciding , if any , on an operation .
the New York Psychiatrist Dr. Jack Drescher , who specializes in the issue of gender identification , said that the new German law &quot; blade after good cause . &quot;
intersexual children are an ethical dilemma .
&quot; some people have life @-@ threatening diseases that require surgical intervention , but most children do not , &quot; he said .
you can do a gender assignment without surgery and then wait to see how the identity develops .
scientific data on how a child develops its gender identity is not very accurate .
nobody knows why it is happening .
it is like the secret why people are homosexual .
a report to the European Commission in 2011 states that intersexual people must be distinguished from transsexuals or transgender persons , because their status is not gender @-@ based , but due to their biological constitution , which is neither male nor female , but typically defines both simultaneously or not clearly as one of them .
these characteristics were reflected in subordinate sexual characteristics such as muscle mass , body , breasts and stature , primary sexual characteristics such as reproductive organs and genitals , or chromosomal structures and hormones .
the report also provides an overview of the discrimination suffered by inter @-@ sexual and transgender persons in professional life and the extent of harassment , violence and prejudice .
boys not in line with the gender picture now have a special camp .
it is now possible for adults in Australia and Nepal to indicate male , female or third sex on official documents .
in June , Australian Norrie May @-@ Welby ( 52 ) was recognized as the world &apos;s first &quot; gender @-@ free &quot; person after a court granted life @-@ long retention of &quot; undefined &quot; gender status .
in addition to M and W , German cards will have a third assignment , X for intersexually , according to the Ministry of the Interior .
in neighbouring France , gender issues are still controversial , according to a news report on France 24 .
in 2011 , dozens of French members of the severely Catholic country signed a petition to remove &quot; gender theory &quot; from school books .
the US site Catholic Online has also spoken out against German law on the grounds that &quot; if the world is broken up into a new state where gender is a choice , but not sexual activity , then we are turning two more pillars of civilisation . &quot;
the mother of a newborn from Maryland explained to baby zone that they would do better if babies were assigned a sex at birth .
&quot; parenthood is stressful enough without further restrictions , especially if you don &apos;t know the sex of your child , &quot; she said .
children need stability and security .
historically , children born with both male and female genders were called hermaphrodites , according to the attractive Greek god who had both sexes .
ten years ago , medicine regarded gender as something that could be extinguished and then rebuilt .
but now the ethical foundations of an operation are being questioned , now that it is known how complex the gender identity is , and that doctors can also be wrong , because they do not know how the child feels when they grow up with the gender they assign .
&quot; in the mid @-@ twentieth century this was called a &quot; psychiatric emergency , &quot; said Drescher .
when such a child was born , it was called not the psychiatrist , but the surgeon .
the ruling theory of treatment of children with undefined genitals is based on Dr. John Money of Johns Hopkins University , who argued that gender is formable .
he shaped the term &quot; gender identity , &quot; arguing that social and environmental attacks - how parents educate a child - interacted with the genes and hormones of a child , shaping whether a person considers himself male or female .
but in a case that became known as &quot; John / Joan &quot; in 1966 , his theories became controversial .
he told the parents of a boy whose penis had been separated from a mutilated circumcision , to cut the child completely and also to remove his trousers and then raise him up as a girl .
&quot; money presented this case as a successful example of transformation , but it was not , &quot; said Drescher .
when the boy was about 15 , he moved back to the male sex and married a woman .
with 38 but he committed suicide .
according to Drescher , there are still doctors who would practice this model .
but in the 1990 &quot; s , with the advent of the Internet , survivors of these sexual operations became public , &quot; unhappy with the result . &quot;
for example , Jim Bruce , a 36 @-@ year @-@ old Montana author born with XY male chromosomes , but ambiguous genitals .
doctors were not clear whether he had a big clitoris or a small penis , and were convinced that he could never lead a &quot; satisfactory life &quot; as a man .
so his external organ and the trousers were surgically removed shortly after birth in 1976 , and he was raised up as a girl .
at the age of 12 he received female hormones .
&quot; I knew I am not a girl , &quot; he told ABCNews.com
I was unhappy , but it was really difficult to ask questions .
at the age of 18 he should receive a vaginal plastic .
but , knowing that something was wrong , he demanded his medical files .
what he found out was shocking .
I was sterilised at my birth - and nobody ever told me .
Bruce was born with a DSD through which his body could not produce enough testosterone to develop the genitals .
after learning the truth , he returned to the male identity , received testosterone injections , and allowed his breasts to be removed .
the operation has made it infertile .
today , he is fighting for others in an organization called Interface Project to ensure that intersexual people are perceived as normal .
but Anne Tamar @-@ Mattis , Managing Director of the California @-@ based Advocates for Informed Choice legal group , is concerned that the German law can &quot; encourage stamps and stigma . &quot;
&quot; many activists are concerned that the German decision could encourage parents to take quick decisions and &quot; assign &quot; the child to the child , she said .
we fear that this will favour intervention .
we think it would be better to allocate the male or female sex and then wait .
but we do not yet know how the law will affect , so we can only speculate .
Tamar @-@ Mattis said her organization supports Australian law , because &quot; it allows adults to be recognised as a third sex . &quot;
she said .
the German law is about attribution at birth .
this is not a fight at which small children should be forced at this time .
when they grow , they can decide their own body .
but Dr. Arlene Baratz , a quagmire scientist from Pittsburg , who has a daughter with a sexual differentiation disorder and who supports hundreds of others in a self @-@ help group , says that the German law &quot; authorises &quot; both parents and children .
Katie , the daughter of Baratz , was born with male chromosomes , but has a DSD called complete androgenic resistance .
because of the recipe defect of the target cells for testosterone , Katie developed female characteristics .
she has a vagina , but no uterus and no ovaries .
today Katie is 29 and married ; she works at the University of Pennsylvania as an employee in child psychiatry .
although it is infertile , it hopes to get a child through adoption or surrogate mother .
&quot; the law gives parents room , so they do not have to take decisions overly , &quot; Baratz said .
it gives them time to make different tests and clarify things and gives them time to write &quot; male &quot; or &quot; female . &quot;
in this way , everything is fine - you pull the child big and love it .
you have a wonderful baby and enjoy the parenthood .
and you do not have to do an operation that can no longer be reversed .
&quot; this includes children in the decision and removes the fear that parents are driving around because they think they are not doing the right thing , &quot; she explained .
ultimately , the child decides on the gender that suits him better - and that is wonderful .
this will enable children to make the decision themselves .
