us to continue prosecuting Snowden
the US has not changed its position as former US intelligence officer Edward Snowden .
he continues to be accused of unauthorised disclosure of secret information .
as a result , he had to face criminal proceedings in the US , said Jennifer Psaki , US Secretary of State spokesperson in Washington .
nor would Snowden &apos;s recent statements change that .
prior to that , after a meeting with Snowden in Moscow , German Green politician Hans @-@ Christian Ströbele called on the US to stop threatening him with punishment .
Psaki stressed that there was a stream of statements by a parliamentarian rather than by a German government member .
in principle , the secret service publisher Edward Snowden is ready to talk to the German authorities .
first , however , he wants his situation to be clarified .
this was made clear by the former US @-@ sought NSA staff in a non @-@ addressed letter published by Green politician Hans @-@ Christian Ströbele on Friday after a meeting with Snowden and forwarded to the Federal Government , Bundestag and the Federal Prosecutor General .
the text of the letter is as follows :
to those responsible
I have been asked to write to you about your inquiry into mass surveillance .
I am Edward Joseph Snowden and I was previously a technical expert at the National Security Agency ( NSA ) , the Central Intelligence Agency ( CIA ) and the Defense Intelligence Agency ( DIA ) of the United States .
in the course of my work in these institutions , I witnessed systematic violations of the law of my government , which led me to act through moral duty .
as a result of the publication of these concerns , I have been exposed to a serious and persistent tendency to leave my family and home .
I live in exile and enjoy temporary asylum granted to me by the Russian Federation under international law .
I am encouraged by the response to my political action , both in the US and elsewhere .
citizens around the world , and also high officials - including the United States - have judged revelations to be a system of overarching surveillance that is accountable to no one as a service to the public .
these espionage revelations resulted in many proposals for new laws and directives aimed at the previously covert abuse of public confidence .
the benefits for society from these findings are becoming increasingly clear , while risks acquired have been deliberately reduced .
although the result of my efforts has been demonstrably positive , my government continues to treat dissent as a fidelity and seeks to criminalise and prosecute political expression .
nevertheless , saying the truth is not a crime .
I am confident that the United States Government , with the support of the international community , will adopt this harmful attitude .
I hope that , when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved , I will be able to participate appropriately and legally in the responsible clarification of the facts relating to the statements made in the media , particularly with regard to the truth and authenticity of the reports .
I look forward to hearing with you in your country as soon as the situation is clarified and thank you for your efforts to respect international law , which protects us all .
Edward Snowden testifies to Hans @-@ Christian Ströbele
