report : Obama campaign to replace Biden with Hillary Clinton
President Barack Obama &apos;s closest advisers , secretly , have considered replacing Vice @-@ President Joe Biden in the 2012 election campaign with Hillary Clinton , according to the New York Times .
the revelation is the most remarkable surprise of the long @-@ awaited work of Mark Halperin and John Heilemann on the 2012 election campaign , &quot; Double Down : game Change 2012 . &quot;
the Times has a copy of the upcoming book , and she reported on Thursday evening that the president &apos;s top advisers had conducted &quot; extensive group meetings and surveys at the end of 2011 &quot; to find out whether Obama &apos;s waning hope of re @-@ election would be better off if he left Biden to fall .
according to Jonathan Martin , Times National Political Correspondent , the book thoroughly tracks the story of the efforts of leading campaign and White House staff , notably former White House Chief of Staff Bill Daley , to measure the effect it has on the poll values that former Secretary of State Clinton has exchanged with the Vice @-@ President .
the potential change was a strictly guarded secret within the campaign infrastructure in Chicago and the Oval Office .
only half a dozen of the president &apos;s closest advisers - including Daley , Obama &apos;s former campaign leader , Jim Messina , and former White House chief adviser David Axelrod , and David Plouffe - knew about the planned change .
&quot; double Down &quot; claims that Daley has been at the forefront of efforts to exchange bids , despite their &quot; close , personal relationship , &quot; before eventually deciding against such a move , after the data showed that Clinton &apos;s candidacy &quot; would not significantly improve Obama &apos;s chances . &quot;
in an interview with Martin Daley , Daley confirmed that the government had actually considered replacing Biden with Clinton .
&quot; I said a whole series of things that should be considered , and that was one of them , &quot; Daley explained to the magazine .
we must remember that the President had terrible survey values then , so we thought : &apos; for God &apos;s will , what are we doing ? &apos;
while Daley described the investigations as &quot; necessary care , &quot; Martin said to CNN Anderson Cooper that during the re @-@ election campaign considerable effort had been made to find out whether such a train was paying off in terms of the ballot box .
&quot; in campaigns , not so much money is spent on surveys and focus groups unless you seriously think about something , &quot; Martin said .
but it is not clear whether Obama knew that his team was thinking about an exchange .
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley whether his boss at the time knew about the potential change .
while Daley stated that he did not believe that the president was &quot; aware &quot; of the possible change , the former chief of staff admitted that it was &quot; possible &quot; for Obama to know .
Martin added that &quot; Double Down &quot; did not provide a definitive answer to the question of whether Obama &apos;s writing table had reached the political explorations .
Cooper asked Martin whether he was serious about Obama not knowing anything about whether Biden should be dropped in the elections .
&quot; possible , &quot; Martin replied .
what happens on the way with my email ?
e @-@ mail actually means electronic letter .
has e @-@ mail , like conventional mail , been technically implemented in the design of the Internet service ?
when designing the early Internet services , the focus was on making communication possible .
therefore , the basic technical protocols have not taken care to create a stable foundation for an listening safe exchange of letters .
therefore , a conventional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter .
if user &quot; Anna &quot; sends an email to &quot; Benni , &quot; are the computers of the two connected directly ?
in the first step , Anna &apos;s email program or browser sends the mail to its service provider &apos;s mail server .
for example , if she has a GMail account , that would be Google .
this mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses .
on the route , the mail can run over several other servers on the Internet .
Bennie can then call the content at his provider .
are conventional e @-@ mails being read on their way through the network ?
most mails are read by software robots on the way .
the sender &apos;s provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an appendix .
a virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems .
in addition , providers check whether this is an annoying and unsolicited spam mail that is immediately deleted or at least sorted out into a spam folder .
do robots have another task ?
for systems like GMail , the robot also detects the information that Google needs to place context advertising .
when Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip , Google may contain links to holiday offers .
do unknown people also read e @-@ mails ?
the likelihood that unauthorised people will read an email is extremely low .
in theory , however , this is possible .
in companies , administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail .
law enforcement authorities and secret services also have legal means to intercept or take note of e @-@ mails .
this includes possible illegal late @-@ night actions .
is it possible to protect e @-@ mails against reading ?
encryption according to the OpenPGP standard can be used to encrypt an e @-@ mail against reading .
with great technical effort it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an e @-@ mail communication so that it is not even possible to recognize who has communicated with whom .
how important are Yahoo and Google on the e @-@ mail market in Germany ?
according to a survey by Convios Consulting in August 2013 , Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mostly privately used postmen .
while the shares of Yahoo @-@ Mail were last down , GMail could significantly increase Google &apos;s share .
mother in the Forest and Mixed pensions
when his brave mother died , a man from Wolfsburg forged a plan .
he welcomed the dead in a forest - and continued to earn their pensions and care money .
a 67 @-@ year @-@ old Wolfsburger buried his dead mother in the forest after police investigations .
first , he concealed the death of the 89 @-@ year @-@ old , then he had spent more than a year and a half .
now the 67 @-@ year @-@ old has to answer for fraud , as a spokesman said on Friday .
so the man hid the woman in a forest near Helmstedt .
the man was already suspected in May : at that time , it became apparent that no medicines were needed for the maternal needy .
the pensioner told the investigators that his mother went to Spain .
