George Kerevan : European unbundling gives Scots the choice
a new day , a new horror story about independence .
this time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership .
this provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a tiled @-@ wire border along the Hadrian Wall .
indeed , the Strathclyde proposal highlighted the potential economic benefits that more freedom of movement would bring in the rest of Europe , but , as expected , this did not matter in the headlines .
nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often turn their tight rules on when it is cheaper for them .
since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area , continued non @-@ compliance with Brussels would be a small concession in return for what the Scots really want .
so no story .
and one that has come so far in the years that it already resembles a fossil : the first time I heard the &quot; independence means passport controls &quot; - at least 40 years ago .
an interesting point is lost in the constant recovery of this ancient history .
why expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe ?
why exchange the London yoke against Brussels , especially now ?
this is the real European news : the great post @-@ war plan to unite Europe has stalled .
with the euro crisis , the European project has officially died .
parties across the EU are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency .
even in Germany , the Euroskeptic party Alternative for Germany - founded only this year - was able to win almost five million votes in the Bundestag elections in September , effectively driving free democrats out of the Bundestag .
there has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe .
but the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point .
because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank , combined with the straitjacket into which the national economy is forced by adherence to the single currency , many people believe that the European project has gone too far .
the euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits - that was only the case in Greece .
instead , the Eurosystem has fixed its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters - and German politicians like to let that happen .
without the possibility of devaluing the local currency , southern Europe finds itself with a built @-@ in productivity disadvantage vis @-@ à @-@ vis Germany .
the only way is to cut wages and public spending - encouraged by Berlin .
behind the current euro and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem .
as a result of the &quot; green &quot; energy directives imposed by Brussels - a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays double for electricity and four times for gas compared with the United States .
this is a smiling cost disadvantage , as we have already seen in Grangemouth .
all wage fixing in the world does not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas .
as a result , there is a revolt , especially in France , the former EU leader .
after the war , France &apos;s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and raise Paris on an equal footing with Washington .
but Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy , and has pushed Europe into its own economic policy , with the French economy struggling .
as a result , Marine Le Pen &apos;s right @-@ wing , anti @-@ EU National Front has just won a decisive post @-@ election , placing the ruling socialists on top of three .
the National Front is now the most popular party in France , with 24 % of the vote - a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that partitioning on the right would automatically bring benefits to the left .
what does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the white French working class ?
it wants to use next year &apos;s EU elections to forge an anti @-@ EU anti @-@ Community currency bloc in the European Parliament .
if the anti @-@ EU parties do well in these elections - and this is very possible - then for the first time such a block could dominate the European Parliament .
that is the point I want to make : in the not too distant future , growing resentment of the EU and the single currency will unite to abolish the euro .
the EU will not disappear , but it will be more like the Europe of ( sovereign ) nations that General de Gaulle favoured .
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may be stuck with the euro , but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies .
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of avoiding the US .
but Washington &apos;s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain alone will be in Atlantic rain .
where is Scotland in all this ?
we can decide to be a region of ( in the end ) Little England .
or we can defend our own economic interests - including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can find themselves in .
I suspect Scotland could do well in a looser European alliance if we retain our own currency .
cooperation with other similar countries is easier in a non @-@ federal Europe of nations .
otherwise , we should consider equating Norway and maintaining our economic independence .
the SNP government in Scotland has - remarkably - won the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 , owing to the rejection of the proposed ( and made ) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory @-@ Lib Dem coalition .
it would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now , only to be forced into austerity by Berlin and Brussels .
early puberty : faster growth
Afro @-@ American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than white age cooperatives , as studies show .
physical changes do not directly mean puberty
there is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
experts believe that epidemic obesity is a trigger for early puberty
the trend towards early puberty is less pronounced among boys
the former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specialized in child health and family issues .
should a mother be concerned if her daughter grows breasts and shamhairs at the age of seven or eight ?
at the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics in Orlando , Florida this week , the paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and were a new standard .
&quot; I spend a lot of time calming parents - usually this is no sign that puberty is now fast , &quot; Kaplowitz explained .
obvious signs of development , such as growing breasts , shrubs and arms , as well as body smell , appear earlier in girls .
however , there was only a slight shift in the age of the menace ( occurrence of the first regular blood ) in the last 40 years .
in the United States , the average age is 12.5 years , slightly less than 12.75 in 1970 .
&quot; when the development of the breasts begins , it takes at least two to three years until the Menarche , &quot; said Kaplowitz , also author of the book &quot; Early puberty in girls : the essential adviser for dealing with this frequently occurring problem . &quot;
time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses .
what is actually the beginning of puberty is controversial , but it is &quot; premature &quot; when the breast increase is accompanied by an eight @-@ year growth boost .
in most cases , the process is slowing down or stagnating - something that a paediatrician can monitor closely .
if more rapid progress is made , tests may be displayed by an endikronologist so that serious problems such as tumour or cyst can be excluded .
there are treatments to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence : the premature ageing of bones , which can ultimately lead to growth and thus small body growth among adults .
the recommendations for medication or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child , the development speed , the growth rate and emotional maturity .
psychosocial aspects are also important .
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs , but he admits : &quot; suppressing puberty can alleviate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls , unlike being their age cooperatives . &quot;
the other big problem is understandable : parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have the period .
&quot; they worry about pregnancy risk or how they handle the hygienic side , &quot; said Kaplowitz .
&quot; it was a shock , &quot; a woman whose daughter got her days with ten .
although there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation , it was emotionally unprepared .
she came frightened and excited from school home because she was the first in her circle of friends .
there are many widely published theories about the causes of premature puberty .
but there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other food , chemicals in the environment , or sexual messages in the media are responsible .
young people come into puberty like girls before .
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity .
he supported the conduct of a study in 2001 on girls aged between six and nine who are linked between body fat and puberty .
other studies support this conclusion , but there are many other factors that played a role .
in that country , Afro @-@ American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than white age cooperatives .
there are different explanations for this .
global seems to be influenced by all sorts of things , from economic conditions to the climate to the genes .
another puzzle : although boys grow face and shame earlier , the trend towards a full @-@ fledged past puberty is not as strong as girls .
other doctors at the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the issue .
the appearance of acne and shamhaar is common even among babies and infants .
&quot; we must be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty , &quot; said Dr. Lawrence Silverman , a paediatric endocrine at Goryeb Children &apos;s Hospital in Morristown , New Jersey .
parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician how to talk to their child .
&quot; this can mean that you have to talk earlier than expected , &quot; says Kaplowitz .
if you stay calm , the child usually responds well .
girls who flock early need the insurance that the process is a normal part of life , even if it occurs earlier than thought .
Jumbo manufacturers dispute large orders over seat width
between leading aircraft manufacturers , there has been a dispute over the breadth of seats in the tourist class on long @-@ haul flights , which is the tone for a bitter clash at Dubai Airshow this month .
the dispute revolves around the number of seats offered to passengers on long journeys in the tourist class - not always those who are most concerned about the airlines , but this designated space is the key to the efficiency of the latest Airbus SAS and Boeing Co .
this week , Airbus called for an industry standard requiring a seat width of at least 46 cm ( 18 &quot; ) in the tourist class , but the US Archrival Boeing says that the airlines should decide .
the dispute comes at a time when aircraft builders are competing to sell even larger versions of their two @-@ engine long @-@ haul aircraft and expect record orders at the event from 17 to 21 November .
the shape of the rear part of the aircraft - especially if there are nine or ten seats - is crucial for the economic results that the new &quot; mini @-@ jet &quot; design should deliver .
Boeing claims that its modernized &quot; 777X &quot; fiber 406 people are in the tourist class , which is more than 17 inches wide , allowing ten per row .
Airbus declares that the competing version of the A350 carries 350 passengers in 18 @-@ inch seats in the tourist class , with nine per row .
aircraft giants often share hiebe with technical details through advertising in the specialist press .
Airbus is now appealing directly to the public at the Dubai Airshow , where 777X is expected to make the race with more than 100 orders .
recently , the company presented an ad that could be the beginning of a new ad war , showing donors an image in which three people are sitting in a restaurant , entitled &apos; would you accept that ? &apos;
&quot; Boeing proposes long @-@ haul flights in Sitzen that are closer than regional Turbo @-@ Props , &quot; says Airbus Sales Director John Leahy .
in view of changed dietary habits , people are getting thicker , but aircraft seats have not changed radically .
between the early 1970 &quot; s , when the Boeing 747 defined modern long @-@ haul travel , and at the end of the century , the weight of the male average American increased by 10 % between 40 and 49 years , according to US Department of Health data .
according to US health statistics , the male average American &apos;s failure range in the 21st century is 100,8 cm .
Airbus says that its rivals are in line with a seat concept from the 1950s , when the average body size of the freshly flown jet set was narrower .
Airbus has carried out investigations showing that an additional duty ( 2.54 cm ) per seat increases sleeping quality by 53 % .
Boeing denies Airbus &apos; figures on the size of the seats and says that it is not up to the manufacturers to decide how airlines balance air fares and facilities .
the company also declares that , according to research , the experience in the aircraft depends on more than the seat width .
&quot; it really means giving airlines flexibility so that they can do what they think they need to be successful , &quot; explains Kent Craver of Boeing .
they do not want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable .
they know their business better than anyone else .
passengers are more free from elbow , but it is becoming increasingly an issue for manufacturers that can affect sales .
behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $ 700 billion after list prices in the coming decades , which could have a lasting impact on the US or European export balance .
as Reuters reported for the first time in July , the seat layout is the driving force behind the battle over the new jets .
both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest two @-@ engine long @-@ haul designs than the market leader in this segment , the 365 @-@ seat Boeing 77 @-@ 300ER .
the statements made by Boeings on the results partly depend on the 777X being compared with the original design of nine seats in the 777 .
the increased cost per unit is still lower than for currently used machines with 10 seats per row .
&quot; Boeing therefore flies more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive in our products , &quot; says Kevin Keniston , Head of passenger comfort at the European Airbus .
on the other hand , analysts , full cabins with 10 seats per row on existing 777s indicated that many passengers chose a closer arrangement , which could be accompanied by cheaper fares .
&quot; eighteen customs seats would be great for passengers , but the reality is that from an economic point of view , the Airbus offer is driven by the threat posed by the 777 , &quot; says Mary Kirby , expert in cabin equipment , founder and editor of Runway Girl Network .
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats , but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose .
the world @-@ leading jet vendors even carry bandwidth to measure the equipment in competition .
even if they praise the comfort , all manufacturers also offer jets with a highly condensed design for low @-@ cost airlines and regional flights .
Airbus has a ten @-@ seat A350 but has not yet sold .
until recently , Airbus stressed the importance of more adaptability of the cabins and offered wide seats to some jets .
without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets , experts say that the call for a new industry standard is likely to puzzle , but could distract from the wave of 777X sales .
new anti @-@ nicotine vaccine could make smoking a success .
scientists have developed an anti @-@ nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking .
a single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for life .
before human testing , further tests are needed , which may take several years , but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said that the first results were good .
&quot; we are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to stop using all the methods available on the market , but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches , &quot; said Cornell .
the new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain genetic information to produce nicotine antibodies .
the virus selectively infects the liver cells , which then produce a constant stream of antibodies .
the antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain , leaving a smoker without a nicotine high .
in experiments , vaccinated mice , to which Nikotin was given , maintained its normal level of activity .
by contrast , mice without vaccination would have taken a &quot; break @-@ out , &quot; the researchers said , a sign that the nicotine had reached their brain .
the experiments are described in Science Translational Medicine .
earlier tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies .
the vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain the antibody level that they were expensive and impractical .
but the cost of the new vaccine is probably much lower , because it transforms liver cells into antibody perfabria .
as Professor Crystal said , a future vaccine for people who are safe could be administered to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette , thereby preventing nicotine addiction .
more likely , smokers would use it to stop .
&quot; they then know : when they start smoking again , they no longer feel pleasure because of nicotine vaccine , and that helps them to leave the habit , &quot; he explains .
British scientists said that the results were interesting , but they warned that further research was needed .
