rules on electronic equipment in aircraft remain in force in Australia for the time being
Australian air passengers must continue to shut off tablets and smartphones when they start and land , despite efforts in the US to ease the rules on such devices .
the US Federal Aviation Administration ( FAA ) allows US airlines to change their standards so that passengers can read , watch or play e @-@ books on their devices during critical flight phases , if they are in &quot; flight mode . &quot;
during most of the flight , passengers are already allowed to do so , but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e @-@ books when starting and landing .
Australian companies are following the decision to implement which the US airlines will have to do a huge amount of work , but are not pursuing immediate plans to amend their rules .
CASA also stated that the announcement would be considered , but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases in Australia remained in force .
&quot; CASA does not currently have specific rules on the use of electronic equipment in aircraft , &quot; has been announced .
the issue is subject to provisions requiring airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow the safety instructions given by cabin crew .
Virgin has already held talks with CASA on the extension of its Wi @-@ Fi entertainment system on flights and has stated that it is open to change , but these must be initiated by the legislator .
&quot; we would welcome a review of the authorisation of electronic devices by CASA , because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after offering ( wireless entertainment ) during the flight , &quot; said a speaker .
Qantas explained that the current rules will continue until further notice .
&quot; our current guidelines stipulate that electronic devices should not be used when starting and landing , and we currently have no plans to change this , &quot; said the company .
the FAA rules apply to US airlines .
however , we are always interested in developments in regulations from which passengers can benefit , and I am sure that the FAA decision and the reasons behind it will be looked closely at .
the decision varies according to the age of the fleet .
they must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio disturbances from mobile devices , and change manuals , training materials , hand luggage programmes and customer support .
&quot; after an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet , it can allow passengers to use portable , light electronic devices such as tablets , e @-@ book readers and smartphones at all levels , &quot; FAA announced .
in rare cases where there is a bad view , the crew will instruct passengers to switch off the equipment during landing .
the group also recommended that heavier equipment be stored safely under the seat or above the seat when landing .
