deposit houses booming in Singapore as the middle class crisis has arrived
in a deposit house in the Bendemeer shopping mall in Singapore , Janani Amirthalinga will exchange a golden wristband , ring and pair of earrings to pay the school fees of their daughters .
&quot; my husband and I have just bought a house , there &apos;s my money there , &quot; says Amirthalinga .
although she earned $ 3,000 a month in Singapore ( about € 1,730 ) as an administrator and her husband also works , the monthly family income is not enough , she explains .
indeed , demand in parts of Southeast Asia - where household indebtedness is increasing - is so large that ValueMax , where she has made her exchange , became the third Pfandhouse listed on the singapurish stock exchange this week .
smuggling is not only a quick way to get money - $ 1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga - but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan .
typically , Pfandhäuser in Singapore require an effective annual rate of 17 % , just above the 15.4 % required by the United Overseas Bank , a local lender with a branch in the same shopping centre .
however , Pfandhäuser offer the advantage that no verification of creditworthiness or evidence of income is required , which is why loans can be made faster than banks .
this is why millions of people in the region are turning to deposit houses after families feel the pressure from rising living costs and growing household and consumer debt .
after five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans , owing to loose fiscal policies in developed economies , families with lower and middle incomes are seeking deposit houses to compensate for the difference in sluggish economies .
this week , the rating agency called Standard &amp; Poor &apos;s growing household debt , mainly through rising mortgages , a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks .
Malaysia , Thailand , and Singapore , according to the agency , have the highest budgetary debt in Asia relative to GDP .
Malaysia is at the top of the list at 80 % of GDP , an increase of 60 % in 2008 .
economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand , which emerged just this week from a technical recession .
on Thursday , the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand .
&quot; in the end , this means that , with rising costs , people in the middle to bottom ( the income scale ) will try to supplement their income wherever possible , &quot; says Song Seng Wun , economist at CIMB , a Malaysian bank .
historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have exacerbated the trend to pledge personal items , as people take the opportunity to turn family jewellery into cash .
in Singapore , about 70 % of the dispossessed items are gold in the 200 deposit houses of the city state .
people say : &quot; the gold price looks good , let us feed grandmother &apos;s gold chain and get back next month . &quot;
easymoney , the largest Thai depositor , has experienced a 20 % increase in customers in its branches in recent months .
growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax , the operator of the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore , wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia - where the company operates four houses - but also outside Asia , said Yeah Lee Ching , Managing Director of ValueMax .
the company finances this with 60 % of the 66 million Singapore dollars it entered this week with the Singapore stock exchange .
while some lenders have gone into the crossfire because of high interest rates , Yeah explains that Pfandbriefe are not only cheaper than other lenders , but also directly increased debt .
&quot; customers are insulting items they already own , and the perverse personal valuables do not increase household debt , &quot; she explains .
the bond business is increasingly accepted socially as short @-@ term , secure financing .
nor are not all people who use Pfandbrief loans in financial difficulties .
rich people from Singapore also come to the branches of ValueMax to feed gold bars and Rolex watches , for which they receive up to 60 % of the purchase price in cash .
our customers come from every social class .
&quot; these include wealthy people who borrow in the short term for a business or investment , or small companies that need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow , &quot; Yeah says .
sometimes they just need money very quickly .
