Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons , according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed important chemical and gas munitions manufacturing facilities , the global chemical weapons monitoring group declared on Thursday , while serious clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored .
also on Thursday , a Syrian group of activists announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed almost three years ago since the civil war began .
the announcement by the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons ( OPCW ) was made one day before the date on
November 1 , which Damascus , based in The Hague , had set up to destroy or &quot; inoperable &quot; all facilities for chemical weapons production , including all machinery for mixing chemicals into toxic gas and filling ammunition .
completing this process , which is essentially the first stage of destruction , is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all Syrian chemical weapons by mid @-@ 2014 .
the destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons .
but Damascus still has to begin to destroy existing weapons and supplies .
according to assumptions , there are about 1,000 tonnes of chemicals and weapons in the country , including Senfgas and the Sarin nerve gas .
the announcement came at a time when fighting took place in Safira on Thursday , when experts said that there was a production facility for chemical weapons and storage facilities , as the UK @-@ based Syrian Human Rights Observatory reported .
the active group , which is following the number of deaths through a network of activists in Syria , declared on Thursday that 120.296 people died .
of these , 61,067 were civilians , including 6,365 children .
on the government side , 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad &apos;s army that 18,678 are pro @-@ government fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias .
also among the dead were 2,202 army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters , many of them foreigners .
on 25 July , the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict to be 100,000 since March 2011 .
this figure has not yet been updated .
the conflict has forced around two million people to flee the country .
Assad &apos;s troops have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels , many of whom have links to al @-@ Qaeda groups .
the observatory said that there were losses on both sides on Thursday , but did not mention details .
the fighting underscores the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors , because their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a dead civil war .
according to the OPCW , which is working closely with the United Nations , the team is now convinced that it has seen and witnessed all the important production and mixing / filling facilities mentioned by Syria . &quot;
therefore , &quot; no further inspection activities are currently planned . &quot;
earlier this week , the inspectors stated that they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 out of 23 sites indicated by Damascus .
the inspectors said that it was not possible to visit two facilities because of security concerns .
on Thursday , OPWC declared that the two sites had been abandoned according to the Syrian statement &quot; and that the existing objects of the chemical weapons programme had been transferred to other such facilities that had been inspected . &quot;
it was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that OPCW inspectors could not visit .
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons , which will have to be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month .
said Ahmed Uzumcu , Director General of the Monitoring Organization in a commentary published by OPCW .
for three years now , mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting Assad &apos;s government and security forces , many of whom belong to the Alawites , to divide Shia Islam .
in view of further developments , the head of the observation group , Rami Abdurrahman , said that on Wednesday there was a strong explosion in an air defence facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia .
he explained .
