FAA : passengers can now use electronic equipment in aircraft ( but not make mobile phone calls )
passengers can now listen to their electronic devices from departure to landing for reading , working , playing , music and using the image of films , but not phone calls , according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration ( FAA ) in the United States on Thursday .
but passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately .
the speed with which they will be implemented depends on the airline , said FAA staff Michael Huerta at a press conference .
the airlines will have to prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new directives and that they have updated the training manuals of the airline staff and the regulations governing the sale of equipment in accordance with the new rules .
FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic equipment in aircraft .
among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue .
&quot; depending on the state of the plan , we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon , &quot; the FAA announced in a statement .
currently , passengers need to switch off smartphones , tablets and other devices when closing aircraft doors .
you may not start it again until the plane reaches a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light .
when entering the landing plane , passengers must turn them off again and not start them again before the plane has landed .
under the new Directives , airlines whose aircraft are protected from electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the equipment even when they start , land and roll @-@ over , said FAA .
most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to larger levels for the use of Wi @-@ Fi should meet the criteria .
Laura Glading , president of professional cabin crew , welcomed the changes .
&quot; if the new regulation is implemented safely - and we are working closely with the airline in this regard - both sides will benefit from it , &quot; commented Glading .
to be honest , we are sorry to have to feel like speeding up this issue .
however , Internet connections for surfing , exchanging e @-@ mails , text messages or downloading data under three kilometres remained prohibited , explained the Authority .
passengers are asked to put smart phones , tablets and other devices into flight mode .
so still no &quot; Words With Friends , &quot; the Scrabble @-@ like online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 , when he had to leave an American Airlines jet publicly because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the fly .
and heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be dust , as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin .
mobile phone calls during the flight will continue to be banned .
the regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission ( FCC ) , not the FAA .
FAA may lift a ban on certain electronic devices when they are launched and landed
last month Mark Rosenker said of the National Transportation Safety Board , safety expert on national transport issues on CBS News , mobile phones are still considered a risk .
&quot; mobile phones are really a problem , not only because they could cause potential disturbances to navigation devices , but because we know from the FCC that the transmission from the air can also disturb transmitters , &quot; says Rosenker .
an industry advisory committee , set up by the FAA to examine this issue , recommended last month that the government allow a broader use of personal electronic devices .
in recent years , pressure on FAA has increased to ease restrictions on use .
critics such as the democratic senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri believe that there are no valid safeguards for the ban .
restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of equipment has become ubiquitous .
some studies say that up to one third of passengers are forgetting or ignoring the switch @-@ off of the device .
the FAA began in 1966 to restrict the use of electronic devices by air passengers , after reports of disturbances of navigation and communication equipment had become known by UKW radios , which were the latest technology trend .
new aircraft are much more dependent on electric systems than previous generations of aircraft , but they are also designed and approved by FAA that do not make them electronic interferences .
airlines have been offering Wi @-@ Fi services to passengers for several years , when the altitude is reached .
air carriers adapted to Wi @-@ Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference .
the vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic equipment under the new directives , said Huerta .
today &apos;s electronic devices generally provide much less radio broadcasting than previous generations .
e @-@ readers , for example , only give up minimal radiation if you look at it .
however , when downloading or sending data , the transmission values are stronger .
Amazon.com.
in 2011 , the company staff invited a passenger aircraft full of Kindle E @-@ Reader and made a test flight to identify problems , but were unable to detect them .
members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment .
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said that he believed that the interference with the equipment was real , even if the risk was minimal .
other committee emitters said that there are only isolated reports from pilots who are in favour of disrupting aircraft systems by the equipment , and most of them are very old .
however , the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange for passengers to switch off the equipment when they arrive under poor visibility .
a group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travellers who would now be equipped with technology .
&quot; we are pleased that FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety , &quot; said Roger Dow , CEO of the U.S. Travel Association .
