in her release , the water rally was fit and healthy .
is Europe &apos;s elite prepared to do business with Britain ?
business for Britain was launched in April with the aim of bringing the economy to the table and defining what those in Britain want to change our relations with the EU .
to this end , we have commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British economic leaders and asked them what they think about Britain , the economy and the EU .
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 executives from the economy , who depict roughly the British companies , sectors , and regions .
the results of the survey will surprise many .
we have found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside Europe , focusing on countries that are modernizing and growing , while the EU states are stagnating .
they want new trade links with countries like China , India , and Brazil to be favoured by government , rather than by the long and demanding process of reforming the obscure EU institutions .
asked for their view on certain legally regulated issues - from antitrust to product legislation - the majority of economic leaders believe that control of these key competences should be brought back to Westminster .
there was general dissatisfaction about the internal market , as companies have said that the costs of Brussels legislation would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe &apos;s trading zone - even 40 % of large companies agreed with what is traditionally the most pro @-@ European .
finally , and this presumably says most , our survey of economic leaders showed that a clear majority of Britain wants a course of change to the agreement and not a relationship with the EU based on trade .
this insight , which is found among companies of all sizes and leading groups , shows that the economy is pushing for a &quot; meaningful change &quot; that brings the book of action back to Britain .
there is much at stake - a change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a 16 % change of opinion in favour of staying in the EU in a referendum .
the Prime Minister should have no doubt : this survey shows that the British economy is behind his plan for renegotiating British conditions for EU membership .
it also shows that companies expect a new negotiation to see a significant shift in power relations back to Britain .
a better deal for the British economy is possible and increasingly necessary now that the eurozone is moving towards closer economic and fiscal union .
the priority must be jobs and growth in Britain , as the result of our survey shows , which means greater focus on trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to rules .
