scientists have been able to shed more light on the context in which the tail of a dog is related to his mood .
earlier research had shown that happy dogs with the tail were more to the right ( from the dog &apos;s point of view ) , while it was the left side for nervous dogs .
but now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences .
Professor Georgio Vallortigara , a neuroscientist at the University of Trento , said : &quot; in humans it is well known that the left and right brains react differently to stimuli that generate positive or negative emotions . &quot;
here we tried to look at this with other species .
he also noted that dogs , like humans , are responsible for the left @-@ wing movement and vice versa , and that the two hemisphere played different roles in feelings .
in order to learn more about how dogs react to the side tail needles of their pets , researchers monitored the animals while these films were watching other dogs .
they measured the heart rate of the violin and analysed the behavior .
we will probably soon understand why the tail moves in one direction or another .
Professor Vallortigara said : &quot; we have shown the dogs movies with dogs - either a natural version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects , and thus we have managed to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right . &quot;
when the animals saw how an otherwise expressive dog moved the tail to the right ( seen from the perspective of the wound dog ) , they remained completely relaxed .
if , however , the tail tendency was mainly left ( again from the point of view of the dog who wounded ) , their heart rate rose and they looked unsettled .
according to Professor Vallortigara , the dogs do not communicate intentionally through these movements .
on the contrary , he is convinced that the dogs had learned from experience which movements they should be concerned about and when not .
he said : &quot; if you have different encounters with other dogs and the wedding is linked to the tail in one direction rather with friendly behavior and the right side produces a less friendly behavior , then you react on the basis of these experiences . &quot;
researchers say that knowledge could help dog owners , veterinarians and trainers to understand the emotions of their animal .
John Bradshaw , an expert in dog behavior and host diplomat at the Faculty of Animal Health at the University of Bristol explained that this was not the first study to examine whether left and right was important for dogs .
last year a team at the University of Lincoln discovered that dogs turn their head to the left when they look at an aggressive dog , and to the right when it is a satisfied dog .
in another research work at the University of Victoria in Canada , it was as follows : &quot; dogs go to a robot dog if they are , tail &quot; on the left and not on the right , instead of getting troubled - exactly the opposite than in the Italian study . &quot;
according to his statement , the differences could therefore prove that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robotics dogs as dogs .
a study of how dogs react to real dogs could help , he explained .
&quot; while there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brains are used for different purposes , many of the details still have to be determined - and dogs are no exception , &quot; says Bradshaw .
however , since their behaviour is simply recorded , it will probably not take long for us to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction , sometimes in the other direction .
