an Obama Spokesman
I have twice elected President Obama in the hope that change is possible
he says that Obama has made commendable efforts , which have been thwarted by Republicans &quot; blockade tactics .
blocking policy does not excuse Obamacare &apos;s website problems , drug attacks
Obama &apos;s memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what could have been done .
Nathaniel P. Morris is a student at Harvard Medical School in the second year .
I am currently reading a terribly sad book .
it is a book that I believed would heal me during the crazy second year of my medical studies and give me hope again .
it is called &quot; The Audacity to Win &quot; and describes Barack Obama &apos;s memoirs for the 2008 presidential election .
when I am finished with my patients &apos; records and go to bed in the evening , the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could smoke the breath .
the election became a landslide victory and news spokesmen held to reflect the historic significance of this hour .
my classmates wept with joy and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find .
a young team of visionaries was on the way to the White House and the nation was ready for change .
when Obama took office in 2008 , he had 82 % approval values .
and then I close the book .
turning back to the present is a bad awakening as if you are pulled out of a dream .
it is hard to remember these optimistic times - they seem to be a vague memory , a sad reminder of missed opportunities .
in the years since I voted for the first time , something has actually changed .
but it is simply nothing I could have imagined .
I acknowledge the great and diverse things Obama has achieved , from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act to the military withdrawal from Iraq , the end of forced disappearance of homosexuality in the army , and the killing of Osama bin Laden .
I agree that party @-@ political blockade tactics have turned too much effort to move our nation forward : immigration reform , a public health @-@ insurance option , and the closure of Guantanamo Bay , to name but a few .
but having defended the Obama administration on countless occasions to colleagues and acquaintances , I ended up trying to explain .
I have reached a point of political despair .
Republican blockade politics cannot explain why foreign leaders are allowed to intercept , or the killing of innocent children by drones in overseas .
it cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans , and why whistleblowers are punished that disclose government misconduct .
it cannot explain why Anwar al @-@ Awlaki , a US citizen , was murdered without trial , and why public funding and spending limits were circumvented during the presidential election .
it does not justify the results of a report which says that the efforts of the White House to suppress the media are the &quot; most aggressive ... since the Nixon government . &quot;
and , more recently , it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act .
I do not know whether this is what I should have expected .
whether I should have understood with 18 that government work could contradict its previous political campaigns .
obviously , the office is not a predictable course , because an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre are shaping public debate .
but if I look at the above examples , they seem to be largely elected by the government itself .
and that disturbs me most .
I re @-@ elected Obama in 2012 , not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy .
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unsophisticated alternative , he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions .
I had the impression that a second term for Obama , free from pressure from future elections , would fulfill the hope that we had been hearing for so long .
but , with Obama &apos;s approval ratings down to less than 45 % this week , that book &apos;s return to 2008 has become all the tougher .
it awakens in me the yearning for the many promises that have broken up in the air .
this week , I read a section of the book describing how Obama had to make a serious loss against Clinton in Pennsylvania &apos;s primary election .
in a meeting with the electors after the decision , he told his staff that they had to get back on track and follow their cause .
he said .
we must remember who we are .
it is five years later , Mr President , and I could not agree more with you .
the views expressed in this comment are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris .
Clive Palmer claims that Prime Minister Tony Abbott has a conflict of interest in parental leave
the billionaire and MEP , Clive Palmer , says that Prime Minister Tony Abbott is in conflict of interest in his parental leave plans because his daughters become pregnant and could therefore benefit from it .
