RBS suspends two Forex traders
the Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange division , two people familiar with the situation ; this is yet another indication that the worldwide official investigation of the alleged manipulation of the currency market is rapidly taking place .
some of the world &apos;s largest banks , including UBS , Barclays , Deutsche Bank , and RBS , confirmed that they are working with the authorities to investigate the world &apos;s largest financial market , where 5.3 billionaires change ownership every day .
the two traders would be the first RBS staff to be suspended in the expanding investigation resulting from the Libyor interbank scandal .
the bank , which did not comment on the suspensions , confirmed this month that it received information requests from authorities .
&quot; our investigation on this issue continues and we cooperate fully with the FCA and other regulators , &quot; said the Bank two weeks ago .
last month , persons close to the situation indicated that RBS forwarded the records of e @-@ mails and instant messages sent by and to a former trader to the UK Supervisory Authority , the Financial Conduct Authority .
this trader , Richard Usher , had left RBS in 2010 and is now expected to have been judged by his current position as European Head of Forex spot trading at JPMorgan .
Rohan Ramchandani , head of the European spot trading at Citi , was judged this week and Matt Gardiner , formerly the leading currency dealer at Barclays and UBS , was suspended at Standard Chartered this week .
none of these traders was accused of misconduct .
Usher &apos;s Instant Message Group included bankers at Barclays and Citigroup , said close people .
UBS announced this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator FINMA had declared that it was seeking a presumed manipulation of the foreign exchange market in a number of Swiss banks .
at least six authorities worldwide - the European Commission , FINMA , the Swiss competition authority WeKo , the FCA , the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are currently dealing with allegations that bankers have agreed on currency market transactions .
HSBC , Citigroup , JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also initiated internal investigations or received information requests from authorities , said people familiar with the situation .
banks cross Instant Messages and emails from several years in search of cases of malpractice .
the news about these investigations has put traders in turmoil in an area that has been one of the most profitable of investment banks &quot; trading units in recent years , but has been under pressure this year because low currency volatility limits speculators &quot; chances .
some bankers have tried to downplay the affair , saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast and highly liquid foreign @-@ exchange market , but leading traders believe that this is not necessarily true .
a leading trader noted that , despite the enormous daily volume of foreign exchange trading , fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the increasing use of banks &apos; own internal platforms lead to &quot; one can influence the market with very low ticket prices . &quot;
the news came out the same day , when Credit Suisse announced that it had cancelled a trader of its London Exchange Traded Funds office this week , after causing a loss of nearly $ 6 million at the end of last year .
the Bank promptly informed the competent authorities and worked with them .
said Credit Suisse .
