Google , Samsung , Huawei over Nortel patents
on Thursday , the group , which owns thousands of former Nortel patents , imposed an avalanche of claims for patent infringement against mobile phone manufacturers , including Google , the company that was outlawed by Nortel in the bankruptcy auction .
Rockstar , the consortium that bought the Nortel patents for $ 4.5 billion , sued Samsung Electronics Co Ltd , HTC Corp , Huawei and four other companies for patent infringement before the U.S. District Court in Texas .
Rockstar is owned by Apple , Microsoft , BlackBerry , Ericsson and Sony .
Google is accused in seven cases of patent infringement .
the patents relate to technology that brings search terms into line with relevant advertising on the Internet , the complaint thus affecting the core of Google &apos;s search engine business .
representatives of Samsung , Huawei , HTC and Rockstar were not directly accessible .
Samsung , Huawei and HTC produce mobile phones that work with Google &apos;s Android operating system , which is in sharp competition with Apple and Microsoft &apos;s mobile products .
in 2011 , Google made an initial bid of $ 900 million for Nortel patents .
Google increased its offer several times and last offered $ 4.4 billion .
after it was outbid by Rockstar &apos;s Nortel patents , Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $ 12.5 billion , a business that was also partly motivated by Motorola &apos;s library of patents .
&quot; although Google has failed in trying to acquire the patent at the auction , Google has violated the patents and continues to do so , &quot;
Rockstar claims that Google &apos;s patent infringement is intentional , according to the accusation .
Egypt &apos;s First freely elected President
Mohammed Morsi sets the rule , but his day of triumph should not mean an end to Egypt &apos;s political disputes .
the Islamist Mohammed Morsi promised a &quot; new Egypt &quot; when he was the first freely elected president of the country to take over the succession of Husni Mubarak , who had been expelled from office 16 months earlier .
with his inauguration at the Supreme Constitutional Court , Morsi became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and Egypt &apos;s fifth head of state since the fall of the monarchy about 60 years ago .
he placed the oath in front of the 18 judges of the court , who had his seat on the Nile , and followed by an ancient Egyptian temple .
&quot; we are striving for a better future , a new Egypt and a second republic , &quot; said Mursi at the solemn ceremony broadcast live on state television .
&quot; today , the Egyptian people have laid the foundations for a new life - absolute freedom , genuine democracy and stability , &quot; said Morsi , a US @-@ trained engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood , a fundamentalist group that had been targeted most of the time since its creation 84 years ago as a banned organization by the government .
hundreds of soldiers and policemen guarded the building when Mursi arrived shortly after 11 o &apos;clock local time in a small car convoy .
only a few hundred followers had gathered in the court to cheer the new president , and , unlike Mubarak &apos;s presidential push , traffic was only temporarily stopped so that the auto convoy could cross the usually busy street that connects the city centre to the southern suburbs .
as an uncharismatic &quot; spare wheel &quot; of the Brotherhood , his personal prestige has increased since his victory and a Friday speech , in which he presented himself not only as a candidate for Islamists , but all those who wanted to achieve the aspirations of the 2011 uprising against authoritarian Mubarak .
&quot; Egypt is today a civilian , national , constitutional , and modern state , &quot; said Morsi , dressed in a blue suit with red collar , told judges in the wood @-@ panelled chamber in which he abandoned his office .
later Mursi went to the University of Cairo where he should give his inaugural address .
he was officially welcomed by an army captain playing the national anthem he heard in his belongings .
the military leader Feldmarschall Hussein Tantawi was present .
on his arrival , he was greeted by hundreds of people present in the university &apos;s largest hearing room , with speakers from &quot; The Army and the People are a hand . &quot;
built in 1908 as a bastion of secular education , the University of Cairo has become a stronghold of Islamic student groups in the 1970s .
on Friday , Morsi set off a symbolic oath in Tahir Square , the birthplace of the uprising that led to the end of Mubarak &apos;s authoritarian rule , and he promised to reclaim presidential powers that the Military Council had assumed by the head of state who was driven out of office .
but by standing before the court and not as usual before Parliament , he is bowing to the will of the military , indicating that the power struggle will continue .
Morsi &apos;s speech in Tahir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures .
