travelling through mud , rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
there are not many doctors in West Africa , only one for 5,000 people .
vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 of the &quot; CNN Heroes of 2013 . &quot;
you can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the Top 10 to elect him to the &quot; CNN Hero of the Year . &quot;
the winner receives $ 250,000 to continue his exceptional work .
for 21 years Georges Bwelve looked at how his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him .
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé , the capital of Cameroon in 1981 .
at first , he had only one broken arm , but then a inflammation was formed that spread to his brain and caused a hematom there that was supposed to affect him for the rest of his life .
&quot; there were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon , &quot; said Georges Bwelle .
we would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had had the money .
instead , Bwelve spent years accompanying his father in overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer .
&quot; it is not easy , &quot; commented Bwelle .
you can leave the house at five o &apos;clock in the morning and drive to the hospital to be the first and not the first .
there are a great many patients .
some people even die because they have to wait .
the situation has hardly changed since Bwelles father died in 2002 .
in Cameroon there is only one doctor for 5,000 people , according to the World Health Organisation .
on the other hand , the relationship in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people .
but even if there were a doctor for her , most Cameroon could not afford to visit .
two out of five people live below the poverty line and nearly three quarters of the country &apos;s health expenditures are private .
&quot; the only problem they have is poverty , &quot; says Bwelle .
and poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life .
to see his father and so many of his compatriots suffering , in a wave , made the decision to do something about it .
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer have carried out 700 free operations last year .
he became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé .
he also founded a non @-@ profit organization called ASCOVIME , which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there .
since 2008 , he and his voluntary group have helped almost 32,000 people .
almost every Friday he and up to 30 people forced themselves into minibuses and drive with the snow @-@ covered medical equipment on the roof over unsecured terrain to the villages that need help .
things are not always going smoothly .
more than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud .
but when they arrive , they will be received as heroes : a celebration , singing and dance and the best accommodation the place has to offer .
in these villages , free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and wave - with its broad smile and limitless energy - at the happy celebration .
the next morning the team will start investigating hundreds of patients .
&quot; we treat 500 people per trip , &quot; says Bwelle .
they come from a distance of 60 kilometres around the village - and that is on foot .
each of these weekend clinics provides medical care in a number of areas .
many people are treated for malaria , tuberculosis , malnutrition , diabetes , parasites and sexually transmitted diseases .
others get clutches , donated glasses , or free birth certificates - a document that is necessary for school , but many poor families simply cannot afford .
in the evening , the team carries out simple operations with local anaesthesia .
the operations usually take place in a school , town hall or apartment ; after the intervention , the patients stand up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next .
the lighting for the OP and the disinfection equipment is fed by the generator of the group and thus work waves and its volunteers until the early hours of the morning on Sunday .
it is a demanding pensum , but village musicians usually help keep the team motivated .
&quot; you drill all night so that we can stay awake and continue our work , &quot; says Bwelle .
on Sunday the team will return to the city , tired but proud of the work done .
the group - a mixture of Cameroon doctors and foreign medical students - carried out 700 free operations last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference for the people they help .
a man explained that the free operation of a corpse that he received now allows him to work again .
&quot; this changes the future of my family , &quot; the man said .
in addition to weekend clinics and his work as surgeon in the hospital , Bwelle also works in private clinics in Yaoundé at night .
with this second job he finances 60 % of his non @-@ profit activity , Bwelle ; the rest comes from private donations .
&quot; I really do not know when he sleeps , &quot; says Katie O &apos;Malley , who studied medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and volunteer in Bwelles Group .
he is always either in hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can go to these campaigns .
for medical and health @-@ care students such as O &apos;Malley , who come from the US and Europe to support waves , this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never have at home .
&quot; we can be involved in operations where we help remove blood or keep the instruments for Dr. Bwelle , &quot; explains O &apos;Malley .
this would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year .
students usually pay for their journey to Cameroon and often bring donated sanitation material .
but once they are in Yaoundé , Bwelle takes over accommodation , transport and instruction .
&quot; he is undoubtedly a hero , &quot; says O &apos;Malley .
he dedicates his life to this organisation and his desire to help the Cameroon people knows no limits .
almost permanent work is not a burden on bystanders .
giving others a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he made to his father gives him great pleasure .
&quot; I am so happy when I do this work , &quot; says Bwelle .
and I am thinking of my father .
I hope he sees what I do .
I do it to bring people to laugh again and to relieve the pain .
visit the ASCOVIME website and learn how to help .
an excellent fight
the role of Santiago , the old man in Hemingways Novelle &quot; The old man and the sea , &quot; Horst Janson is cut onto the body .
Janson is himself an old hase in his metier , the acting art .
the old man Santiago cannot pretend anything about fishing .
so the two simply complement each other great .
