tourism : descent to the Romans
a sewage channel from the Roman era is preserved below Cologne at about 120 metres .
if you visit Cologne , don &apos;t miss the cathedral .
the two towers rise into the sky about 157 metres , making it the second @-@ highest church building in Europe .
but only a few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers understand that there is also a lot to discover under the Duomo .
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne .
meeting point for his tours is the service center of Cologne @-@ Tourism directly at the Duomo .
the tour starts unspectacularly : &quot; we start in the underground garage , &quot; says Schulze .
in the seventies , the city &apos;s founders wanted an autochthonous city , and therefore the remains of the old city wall only stood what was not too big .
for this reason , most users of the car park are now also passing the Roman remnants and only leaving their car .
but if you look more closely , the D2 Parkdeck will discover an archaeological site separated by metal grids .
there are about five meters high ruins of handcrafted stones .
&quot; it is the remains of the Roman city wall built after Christ in the second half of the first century , &quot; says Schulze .
before it goes back to the daylight , the students at the upper parking level take a look into a dark , 15 @-@ metre deep shaft .
this is the well of the old dome , which is unfortunately hardly seen .
the next stop of the tour is the Pretorium , and here the participants descend back to the depth .
here we see the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps , the head of the CCAA .
what CCAA means is what a visitor wants to know .
&quot; the abbreviation stands for &quot; Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium , &quot; which in well German means &quot; City of Roman Law and City of Agrippinenser , founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the Empress Choir . &quot;
and the Pretorium is the former palace of statutes , the centre of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine .
from the hall of the exhibition there is a tunnel access to the Roman sewage channel , which is preserved here at about 120 metres .
&quot; you can walk a piece along the so @-@ called Cloaca Maxima if you want , &quot; says Schulze .
there is still one surprise .
after picking up the key at the checkout , he will lead the group to a 16 @-@ metre @-@ deep , accessible shaft .
&quot; we are now in the Mikwe , a ritual Jewish bath , &quot; he explains .
the Jewish community built their bathroom deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was essential for ritual washing .
to this day , in the lower end of the Mikwe , whose origins date back to the eighth century , different water levels can be read through changing levels of the Rhine .
the Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square for which the construction work will begin shortly .
however , a number of years will elapse until completion .
