John Kerry declares in an unprecedented admission that US espionage has &quot; gone too far &quot;
John Kerry indicated , with an unexpected admission , that the US &apos;s defensive stance on its surveillance programs was &quot; inappropriate &quot; in certain cases .
the Foreign Minister also admitted that he , together with Barack Obama , was responsible for switching to &quot; Autopilot &quot; when the explosive revelations of the Whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA &apos;s spy activities became public .
with the leaked information , the US government has come into a diplomatic storm of indignation from its allies .
in a video @-@ linked speech at the Open Government Conference in London , Kerry said : &quot; there is no question that the President and I , and others in the government , have heard of a number of things that have gone out almost by autopilot , simply because there was the ability to do what happened to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War and , of course , 11 September . &quot;
he then admitted , as the first high @-@ level member of the US administration , that US espionage had crossed a border , but also stressed that no rights had been abused .
he said : &apos; in some cases this has gone too far &apos; .
the President is determined to clarify matters and is therefore carrying out a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place .
I assure you that the rights of innocent people will not be affected in this process .
however , Kerry insisted that the NSA was a force of good and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations .
he added : &quot; we are dealing with a new world in which people are prepared to escape into the air . &quot;
there is a radical extremism in the world that is anxious to kill people , flee into the air and attack governments .
so what if we were able to catch and stop this before it happens ?
we have indeed prevented aircraft crashes , attacks on buildings and the murder of people , because we have heard about such plans in advance .
meanwhile , US legislators will travel to Europe to allay concerns about alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to cooperate with the US in the fight against terrorism , as the Chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday .
Senator Chris Murphy from Connecticut said that he spoke to representatives of the European Parliament and other people this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti @-@ terrorist organisations as a result of the frustration with the National Security Agency &apos;s monitoring .
&quot; it is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain on board as regards our joint efforts against terrorism , &quot; said Murphy , who is a democrat in the Senate for the first time and is chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on External Relations and European Affairs , in an interview in Washington .
I also go to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism , regardless of their anger about the NSA programmes .
media reports , according to which the NSA has collected millions of telephone data in Europe , have burdened relations with some US allies , although the head of the secret service said this week that the reports were incorrect and were based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States .
other revelations cited in Snowden &apos;s documents that the NSA monitored Chancellor Angela Merkel &apos;s mobile phone and up to 34 other leaders worldwide .
the head of the national secret services , James Clapper , defended espionage with allies as necessary and declared that this was common on both sides .
in all this turmoil , Murphy said that his authority was preparing the Congress &apos;s trip to be held this year and hoped that the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers .
the names of the other Members participating will be published in the coming days .
he said that the exact route is still being developed .
while Murphy stressed that the purpose of the journey was to improve relations , he also said that there would be some &quot; serious words . &quot;
he said that European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programmes they have been using for years .
&quot; while we can change our surveillance programmes to better protect the rights of Europeans , they must also accept the fact that we are not the only ones to spy , &quot; Murphy says .
meanwhile , John Kerry is on a weekend trip to the Middle East and Poland to deal with the resentment of the US strategy in Syria , Egypt , and Iran , as well as US surveillance activities .
